{"title_page": "MV Coelleira", "text_new": "'''MV ''Coelleira''''' was a Spanish-owned fishing vessel which was built in 1970.{{sfn|Marine Traffic|}} It was wrecked on 4 August 2019 on the [[Ve Skerries]], [[Shetland]].\n\n{|{{Infobox ship begin <!-- commercial vessels -->\n| infobox caption = <!-- keywords: yes, nodab; or caption text -->\n| display title = MV ''Coelleira''\n}}\n{{Infobox ship image\n| Ship image = \n| Ship image size = \n| Ship caption = \n}}\n{{Infobox ship career\n| Hide header = \n| Ship launched = \n| Ship fate = Wrecked on [[Ve Skerries]], [[Shetland]] 4 August 2019\n| Ship identification = * {{IMO number|7023063}}\n* {{MMSI|235215000}}\n* Call sign GHXZ\n* OB93\n| Ship in service = \n| Ship maiden voyage = \n| Ship acquired = \n| Ship christened = \n| Ship completed = \n| Ship laid down = \n| Ship name = *''Coelleira'' (2007-2019)\n*''Poolster'' (?-2007)\n| Ship way number = \n| Ship yard number = \n| Ship original cost = \n| Ship builder = \n| Ship ordered = \n| Ship registry = {{flag|United Kingdom|civil}} ([[Oban]])\n| Ship operator = \n| Ship owner = Blue Pesca Limited\n| Ship notes = \n}}\n{{Infobox ship characteristics\n| Hide header = \n| Ship depth = \n| Ship crew = \n| Ship capacity = \n| Ship speed = \n| Ship propulsion = \n| Ship power = \n| Ship ice class = \n| Ship ramps = \n| Ship deck clearance = \n| Ship decks = \n| Ship draft = \n| Header caption = \n| Ship draught = \n| Ship height = \n| Ship beam = {{convert|6.91|m|ft}}\n| Ship length = {{convert|30|m|ft}}\n| Ship displacement = \n| Ship tonnage = {{GT|210}}\n| Ship type = [[Longline fishing|Longline]] [[fishing vessel]]\n| Ship class = \n| Ship notes = \n}}\n|}\n\n== Wrecking ==\n[[File:Coelleira_wrecked_on_the_Clubb,_Ve_Skerries_pre_salvage_attempt.jpg|thumb|''Coelleira'' aground on the Clubb before the salvage attempt]]\nLate on 3 August 2019, the UK-registered, Spanish-owned fishing vessel ''Coelleira'' was returning to [[Scrabster]] from about {{Convert|18|nmi|km mi|abbr=}} north of [[Yell Sound]]'s entrance{{sfn|MAIB|2020|p=2}} with a catch of approximately 15 tonnes of fish.{{sfn|MAIB|2020|p=4}} Apart from the low light, the conditions were ideal - there was clear visibility, smooth seas and light winds. With the intention of returning as quickly as possible (due to unexpected delays in their fishing operations), the ship's mate set the vessel on a heading of 184\u00b0 and proceeded at a speed of {{convert|9|kn|km/h mph|abbr=}} to keep close to the coast in order to save time. At 21:42 the heading was set to 204\u00b0.{{sfn|MAIB|2020|p=2}}\n\nAt 22:30 the skipper (a 56-year-old Spanish national){{sfn|MAIB|2020|p=7}} took over watch from the mate, who went to bed. The skipper over the next 2 hours made five adjustments to the ships' heading in order to follow the coast. The skipper during this time worked on fish landing records and other managerial work. It is not known how often the vessel's position was checked.{{sfn|MAIB|2020|p=2}}\n\nAt 00:23 on 4 August, vessel was set to heading of 206\u00b0 with the aim of keeping around {{Convert|3.5|nmi|km mi|abbr=}} away from any navigational risk. The skipper did not see any hazards on the [[chartplotter]], and while he did see a [[lighthouse]] light towards the port bow, he assumed it was a lighthouse on the mainland.{{sfn|MAIB|2020}}\n\nAt an unspecified time, the skipper left the [[Bridge (nautical)|wheelhouse]], and (according to a [[Marine Accident Investigation Branch]] report) while the skipper was returning to his post at 01:24, ''Coelleira'' ran aground on the Clubb, [[Ve Skerries]] travelling at {{convert|10|kn|km/h mph|abbr=}}. The crew awoke with the sound of the collision, whereupon they assembled in the wheelhouse and donned [[Survival suit|survival suits]] and [[life jackets]]. Two lifeboats were launched off the starboard side.{{sfn|MAIB|2020|p=2}} At 01:29 the Shetland [[Her Majesty's Coastguard|Coastguard]] were notified of the accident, and in response the [[Aith]] lifeboat and a rescue helicopter were sent to the scene. All 15{{sfn|MAIB|2020|p=12}}{{sfn|Shetland Times|2019}} crew were winched aboard the helicopter, and were returned to emergency landing site at Clickimin in [[Lerwick]] uninjured.{{sfn|MAIB|2020|p=4}}\n[[File:Coelleira_wrecked_on_the_Clubb,_Ve_Skerries_post_salvage_attempt.jpg|left|thumb|''Coelleira'' on its port side after the salvage attempt]]\nAttempts were subsequently made to refloat the vessel. The ship was surveyed with assistance from the [[Sullom Voe Terminal]] tug ''Tystie'', however during the inspection the vessel rolled 5-10\u00b0 to port, at which point the men aboard were evacuated.{{sfn|MAIB|2020|p=4-5}} The emergency towing vessel ''Ievoli Black'' attempted to pull ''Coelleira'' off the Clubb on 7 August, however during the attempt the ship tilted over 55\u00b0 to port, and with a forecast of poor sea conditions and weather the ship was deemed unsalvageable. In the following days the ship broke up and sank.{{sfn|MAIB|2020|p=5}}\n\nIn its report on the incident, the [[Marine Accident Investigation Branch]] concluded that the planning of the passage between the fishing grounds and Scrabster was inadequate, the ship's position was not kept track of, and bridge was empty when the ship went aground. They posed that the skipper's decision making may have been impacted by fatigue, while the set up of the bridge's controls may have made it more difficult to observe risks to the ship.{{sfn|MAIB|2020|p=1}}\n\n== See also ==\n\n* [[Ve Skerries]]\n* [[List of shipwrecks in 2019]]\n* [[List of shipwrecks of the United Kingdom]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== Sources ==\n{{refbegin}}\n*{{Cite web|url=https://www.marinetraffic.com/en/ais/details/ships/shipid:202176/mmsi:235215000/imo:7023063/vessel:COELLEIRA|title=Coelleira|last=|first=|date=|website=Marine Traffic|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-10|ref={{harvid|Marine Traffic|}}}}\n*{{Cite web|url=https://www.shetlandtimes.co.uk/2019/08/04/fifteen-rescued-after-boat-runs-aground|title=Fifteen rescued after boat runs aground|date=2019-08-04|website=The Shetland Times|url-status=live|access-date=2020-04-10|ref={{harvid|Shetland Times|2019}}}}\n*{{Cite report|url=https://assets.publishing.service.gov.uk/media/5e73aba6d3bf7f467a27a17b/2020-08-Coelleira.pdf|title=Stranding and loss of the fishing vessel ''Coelleira'' (OB 93) Ve Skerries, Shetland 4 August 2019|date=March 2020|publisher=Marine Accident Investigation Branch|issue=8/2020|access-date=2020-03-22|format=PDF|ref={{harvid|MAIB|2020}}}}\n\n{{refend}}\n\n{{coord|60.3693|N|1.8265|W|display=title}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Coelleira}}\n[[Category:1970 ships]]\n[[Category:Ships sunk in collisions]]\n[[Category:Ships sunk with no fatalities]]\n[[Category:Fishing vessels of the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Fishing history of Shetland]]\n", "text_old": "'''MV ''Coelleira''''' was a Spanish-owned fishing vessel which was built in 1970.{{sfn|Marine Traffic|}} It was wrecked on 4 August 2019 on [[Ve Skerries]], [[Shetland]].\n\n{|{{Infobox ship begin <!-- commercial vessels -->\n| infobox caption = <!-- keywords: yes, nodab; or caption text -->\n| display title = MV ''Coelleira''\n}}\n{{Infobox ship image\n| Ship image = \n| Ship image size = \n| Ship caption = \n}}\n{{Infobox ship career\n| Hide header = \n| Ship launched = \n| Ship fate = Wrecked on [[Ve Skerries]], [[Shetland]] 4 August 2019\n| Ship identification = * {{IMO number|7023063}}\n* {{MMSI|235215000}}\n* Call sign GHXZ\n* OB93\n| Ship in service = \n| Ship maiden voyage = \n| Ship acquired = \n| Ship christened = \n| Ship completed = \n| Ship laid down = \n| Ship name = *''Coelleira'' (2007-2019)\n*''Poolster'' (?-2007)\n| Ship way number = \n| Ship yard number = \n| Ship original cost = \n| Ship builder = \n| Ship ordered = \n| Ship registry = {{flag|United Kingdom|civil}} ([[Oban]])\n| Ship operator = \n| Ship owner = Blue Pesca Limited\n| Ship notes = \n}}\n{{Infobox ship characteristics\n| Hide header = \n| Ship depth = \n| Ship crew = \n| Ship capacity = \n| Ship speed = \n| Ship propulsion = \n| Ship power = \n| Ship ice class = \n| Ship ramps = \n| Ship deck clearance = \n| Ship decks = \n| Ship draft = \n| Header caption = \n| Ship draught = \n| Ship height = \n| Ship beam = {{convert|6.91|m|ft}}\n| Ship length = {{convert|30|m|ft}}\n| Ship displacement = \n| Ship tonnage = {{GT|210}}\n| Ship type = [[Longline fishing|Longline]] [[fishing vessel]]\n| Ship class = \n| Ship notes = \n}}\n|}\n\n== Wrecking ==\n[[File:Coelleira_wrecked_on_the_Clubb,_Ve_Skerries_pre_salvage_attempt.jpg|thumb|''Coelleira'' aground on the Clubb before the salvage attempt]]\nLate on 3 August 2019, the UK-registered, Spanish-owned fishing vessel ''Coelleira'' was returning to [[Scrabster]] from about {{Convert|18|nmi|km mi|abbr=}} north of [[Yell Sound]]'s entrance{{sfn|MAIB|2020|p=2}} with a catch of approximately 15 tonnes of fish.{{sfn|MAIB|2020|p=4}} Apart from the low light, the conditions were ideal - there was clear visibility, smooth seas and light winds. With the intention of returning as quickly as possible (due to unexpected delays in their fishing operations), the ship's mate set the vessel on a heading of 184\u00b0 and proceeded at a speed of {{convert|9|kn|km/h mph|abbr=}} to keep close to the coast in order to save time. At 21:42 the heading was set to 204\u00b0.{{sfn|MAIB|2020|p=2}}\n\nAt 22:30 the skipper (a 56-year-old Spanish national){{sfn|MAIB|2020|p=7}} took over watch from the mate, who went to bed. The skipper over the next 2 hours made five adjustments to the ships' heading in order to follow the coast. The skipper during this time worked on fish landing records and other managerial work. It is not known how often the vessel's position was checked.{{sfn|MAIB|2020|p=2}}\n\nAt 00:23 on 4 August, vessel was set to heading of 206\u00b0 with the aim of keeping around {{Convert|3.5|nmi|km mi|abbr=}} away from any navigational risk. The skipper did not see any hazards on the [[chartplotter]], and while he did see a [[lighthouse]] light towards the port bow, he assumed it was a lighthouse on the mainland.{{sfn|MAIB|2020}}\n\nAt an unspecified time, the skipper left the [[Bridge (nautical)|wheelhouse]], and (according to a [[Marine Accident Investigation Branch]] report) while the skipper was returning to his post at 01:24, ''Coelleira'' ran aground on the Clubb, [[Ve Skerries]] travelling at {{convert|10|kn|km/h mph|abbr=}}. The crew awoke with the sound of the collision, whereupon they assembled in the wheelhouse and donned [[Survival suit|survival suits]] and [[life jackets]]. Two lifeboats were launched off the starboard side.{{sfn|MAIB|2020|p=2}} At 01:29 the Shetland [[Her Majesty's Coastguard|Coastguard]] were notified of the accident, and in response the [[Aith]] lifeboat and a rescue helicopter were sent to the scene. All 15{{sfn|MAIB|2020|p=12}}{{sfn|Shetland Times|2019}} crew were winched aboard the helicopter, and were returned to emergency landing site at Clickimin in [[Lerwick]] uninjured.{{sfn|MAIB|2020|p=4}}\n[[File:Coelleira_wrecked_on_the_Clubb,_Ve_Skerries_post_salvage_attempt.jpg|left|thumb|''Coelleira'' on its port side after the salvage attempt]]\nAttempts were subsequently made to refloat the vessel. The ship was surveyed with assistance from the [[Sullom Voe Terminal]] tug ''Tystie'', however during the inspection the vessel rolled 5-10\u00b0 to port, at which point the men aboard were evacuated.{{sfn|MAIB|2020|p=4-5}} The emergency towing vessel ''Ievoli Black'' attempted to pull ''Coelleira'' off the Clubb on 7 August, however during the attempt the ship tilted over 55\u00b0 to port, and with a forecast of poor sea conditions and weather the ship was deemed unsalvageable. In the following days the ship broke up and sank.{{sfn|MAIB|2020|p=5}}\n\nIn its report on the incident, the [[Marine Accident Investigation Branch]] concluded that the planning of the passage between the fishing grounds and Scrabster was inadequate, the ship's position was not kept track of, and bridge was empty when the ship went aground. They posed that the skipper's decision making may have been impacted by fatigue, while the set up of the bridge's controls may have made it more difficult to observe risks to the ship.{{sfn|MAIB|2020|p=1}}\n\n== See also ==\n\n* [[Ve Skerries]]\n* [[List of shipwrecks in 2019]]\n* [[List of shipwrecks of the United Kingdom]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== Sources ==\n{{refbegin}}\n*{{Cite web|url=https://www.marinetraffic.com/en/ais/details/ships/shipid:202176/mmsi:235215000/imo:7023063/vessel:COELLEIRA|title=Coelleira|last=|first=|date=|website=Marine Traffic|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-10|ref={{harvid|Marine Traffic|}}}}\n*{{Cite web|url=https://www.shetlandtimes.co.uk/2019/08/04/fifteen-rescued-after-boat-runs-aground|title=Fifteen rescued after boat runs aground|date=2019-08-04|website=The Shetland Times|url-status=live|access-date=2020-04-10|ref={{harvid|Shetland Times|2019}}}}\n*{{Cite report|url=https://assets.publishing.service.gov.uk/media/5e73aba6d3bf7f467a27a17b/2020-08-Coelleira.pdf|title=Stranding and loss of the fishing vessel ''Coelleira'' (OB 93) Ve Skerries, Shetland 4 August 2019|date=March 2020|publisher=Marine Accident Investigation Branch|issue=8/2020|access-date=2020-03-22|format=PDF|ref={{harvid|MAIB|2020}}}}\n\n{{refend}}\n\n{{coord|60.3693|N|1.8265|W|display=title}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Coelleira}}\n[[Category:1970 ships]]\n[[Category:Ships sunk in collisions]]\n[[Category:Ships sunk with no fatalities]]\n[[Category:Fishing vessels of the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Fishing history of Shetland]]\n", "name_user": "Griceylipper", "label": "safe", "comment": "missing \"the\"", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/MV_Coelleira"}
{"title_page": "Grand Prix 4", "text_new": "{{Infobox video game\n|title     = Grand Prix 4\n|image     = Grand Prix 4 Coverart.png\n|developer = [[MicroProse|MicroProse Chipping Sodbury]] \n|publisher = [[Atari, SA|Infogrames]]\n|designer  = [[Geoff Crammond]]\n|composer  = [[James Hannigan]]\n|engine    = \n|series    = \n|released  = {{vgrelease|EU|June 21, 2002|NA|September 10, 2002}}\n|genre     = [[Sim racing|Racing simulation]]\n|modes     = [[Single-player video game|Single-player]], [[Multiplayer video game|Multiplayer]]\n|platforms = [[Microsoft Windows]]\n}}\n\n'''''Grand Prix 4''''', commonly known as '''''GP4''''', was released for the PC on June 21, 2002, is currently the last [[Formula One]] [[racing simulator]] released by the developer [[Geoff Crammond]] and the [[MicroProse]] label. Based on the [[2001 Formula One season]], GP4 essentially serves as a graphical and seasonal update of ''[[Grand Prix 3]]'' which had been released in 2000. The game retained the series' legendary [[physics engine]]. However it entered the market at a far less hospitable time than its three predecessors, and the game faced stiff competition from an alternative Formula One simulation from studios such as [[Image Space Incorporated|ISI]].\n\n== Modifications from version 3 ==\n\n{{Unreferenced section|date=March 2020}}\n''Grand Prix 4'' featured a heavily revised graphics [[Game engine|engine]] and updated physics including wet weather driving that even today is considered some of the best to ever feature in a motorsport simulation. Despite this, the game still showed Crammond's oft-commented dated approach to game design.\n\n* While it is possible to play the game on a [[Local area network|LAN]], [[multiplayer]] internet gameplay was not possible, due to licensing restrictions. Some individuals managed to circumvent this limitation later using the Free Tunngle Network.\n* The locked framerate and [[CPU]]-heavy graphics were still a big issue with the series despite a completely revised graphics engine. However, the graphics engine proved to be very scalable, supporting models and textures multiple times the detail of the original shipped materials.\n* The mod community faced similar frustrations with the track format and it took fully two years before the track format was truly \"cracked\". The first add-on tracks to be released for the game included [[Shanghai International Circuit|Shanghai]], [[Istanbul Park|Istanbul]] and [[Circuito de Jerez|Jerez]].\n* When the game was initially launched, it had a large number of [[Software bug|bugs]]. Many of these were addressed by a [[Patch (computing)|patch]] which was later included with the retail game, though the project was canned when Microprose closed and no further official fixes were forthcoming. To compensate for this some third party programmers addressed some of the remaining problems, and included enhancements which allowed the game to follow the updated rules of the Formula One championship.\n* Many claimed that the stated \"minimum requirements\" were set too low and that they could barely get the game to run on a significantly more powerful system.\n\nAlthough the game could be considered a relatively modest commercial success the chances of a further entry to the series could be considered slim to none because MicroProse's parent company [[Atari, SA|Infogrames]] dissolved the developer shortly after the game's release. Also, the [[Sony Interactive Entertainment|Sony Computer Entertainment]] brand's exclusive licensing deal for Formula One games rules out an update with official stats. An [[Xbox (console)|Xbox]] port of the title had been planned for release in late 2002 before being cancelled in October of that year.<ref>{{Cite magazine |title=In the chair with Geoff Crammond |magazine=[[Retro Gamer]] |publisher=[[Imagine Publishing]] |issue=69 |page=88}}</ref>\n\n== Reception ==\n{{Video game reviews\n| MC = 77/100<ref name=\"MC\">{{Cite web |title=Geoff Crammond's Grand Prix 4 for PC Reviews |url=https://www.metacritic.com/game/pc/geoff-crammonds-grand-prix-4 |website=[[Metacritic]] |publisher=[[CBS Interactive]] |accessdate=May 13, 2013}}</ref>\n| CGM = {{Rating|3|5}}<ref>{{Cite magazine |title=Grand Prix 4 |magazine=[[Computer Games Magazine]] |publisher=[[theGlobe.com]] |issue=146 |date=January 2003 |page=77}}</ref>\n| CGW = {{Rating|4.5|5}}<ref>{{Cite magazine |last=Smolka |first=Rob |title=Grand Prix 4 |url=http://www.cgwmuseum.org/galleries/issues/cgw_221.pdf |magazine=[[Computer Gaming World]] |publisher=[[Ziff Davis]] |issue=221 |date=December 2002 |page=124 |accessdate=February 16, 2019}}</ref>\n| EuroG = 10/10<ref>{{Cite web |last=Bramwell |first=Tom |date=July 7, 2002 |title=Grand Prix 4 |url=https://www.eurogamer.net/articles/r_gp4 |website=[[Eurogamer]] |publisher=Gamer Network |accessdate=February 16, 2019}}</ref>\n| GSpot = 8/10<ref>{{Cite web |last=Ajami |first=Amer |date=September 11, 2002 |title=Geoff Crammond's Grand Prix 4 Review [date mislabeled as \"September 12, 2002\"] |url=https://www.gamespot.com/reviews/geoff-crammonds-grand-prix-4-review/1900-2879976/ |website=[[GameSpot]] |publisher=CBS Interactive |accessdate=February 16, 2019}}</ref>\n| GSpy = {{Rating|4.5|5}}<ref>{{Cite web |last=Fryman |first=Avi |date=October 18, 2002 |title=GameSpy: Geoff Crammond's Grand Prix 4 |url=http://pc.gamespy.com/pc/grand-prix-4/543802p1.html |website=[[GameSpy]] |publisher=IGN Entertainment |accessdate=February 16, 2019}}</ref>\n| GameZone = 8.5/10<ref>{{Cite web |last=Lafferty |first=Michael |date=September 16, 2002 |title=Grand Prix 4 Review |url=http://pc.gamezone.com/gzreviews/r20314.htm |website=GameZone |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080125041007/http://pc.gamezone.com/gzreviews/r20314.htm |archivedate=January 25, 2008 |url-status=dead |accessdate=February 16, 2019}}</ref>\n| IGN = 8.3/10<ref>{{Cite web |last=Magruder |first=Randy |date=September 12, 2002 |title=Grand Prix 4 Review |url=https://www.ign.com/articles/2002/09/12/grand-prix-4-review |website=[[IGN]] |publisher=Ziff Davis |accessdate=February 16, 2019}}</ref>\n| JXV = 15/20<ref>{{Cite web |author=Jihem |date=June 21, 2002 |title=Test: Grand Prix 4 |url=http://www.jeuxvideo.com/articles/0000/00002214_test.htm |language=French |website=[[Jeuxvideo.com]] |publisher=Webedia |accessdate=February 16, 2019}}</ref>\n| PCGUS = 73%<ref>{{Cite magazine |last=Mahood |first=Andy |title=Grand Prix 4 |url=http://www.pcgamer.com/archives/2005/07/grand_prix_4.html |magazine=[[PC Gamer]] |publisher=[[Future US]] |volume=9 |issue=12 |date=December 2002 |page=98 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20060315132101/http://www.pcgamer.com/archives/2005/07/grand_prix_4.html |archivedate=March 15, 2006 |url-status=dead |accessdate=February 16, 2019}}</ref>\n| PCZone = 86%<ref>{{Cite web |last=Presley |first=Paul |date=August 5, 2002 |title=PC Review: Grand Prix 4 |url=http://www.computerandvideogames.com/article.php?id=77713 |website=[[PC Zone]] |publisher=[[Future plc]] |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070630230146/http://www.computerandvideogames.com/article.php?id=77713 |archivedate=June 30, 2007 |url-status=dead |accessdate=February 16, 2019}}</ref>\n}}\n\n''Grand Prix 4'' received \"generally favorable reviews\" according to the [[Review aggregator|review aggreation]] website [[Metacritic]].<ref name=\"MC\"/>\n\nThe game won the award in the Sports category at the [[British Academy of Film and Television Arts]] Awards in 2002.<ref>{{cite web |title=Interactive {{!}} Games - Sport in 2002 |url=http://awards.bafta.org/award/2002/interactive/games-sport |website=[[British Academy of Film and Television Arts]]}}</ref> It was also nominated for ''[[Computer Gaming World]]''{{'}}s 2002 \"Sports Game of the Year\" award, which ultimately went to ''[[Madden NFL 2003]]''. The editors called ''Grand Prix 4'' \"one of the better racing games in years past\".<ref>{{Cite magazine |author=CGW staff |title=Computer Gaming World's 2002 Games of the Year (Sports Game of the Year) |url=http://www.cgwmuseum.org/galleries/issues/cgw_225.pdf |magazine=Computer Gaming World |publisher=Ziff Davis |issue=225 |date=April 2003 |page=94 |accessdate=February 16, 2019}}</ref>\n\n{{clear}}\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{moby game|id=/windows/grand-prix-4}}\n*{{dmoz|Games/Video_Games/Driving_and_Racing/Simulations/Formula_1_Grand_Prix_Series/Grand_Prix_4|''Grand Prix 4''}}\n*[http://www.gp4central.com/ GP4 Central] - A fan site\n*[http://www.grandprixgames.org Grand Prix Games - The Community Place] - A fan forum\n*[http://gp4forever.com GP4 Forever] - A fan forum\n\n<!--==========================({{NoMoreLinks}})============================\n    | PLEASE BE CAUTIOUS IN ADDING MORE LINKS TO THIS ARTICLE. WIKIPEDIA  |\n    | IS NOT A COLLECTION OF LINKS NOR SHOULD IT BE USED FOR ADVERTISING. |\n    |                                                                     |\n    |           Excessive or inappropriate links WILL BE DELETED.         |\n    | See [[Wikipedia:External links]] & [[Wikipedia:Spam]] for details.  |\n    |                                                                     |\n    | If there are already plentiful links, please propose additions or   |\n    | replacements on this article's discussion page. Or submit your link |\n    | to the relevant category at the Open Directory Project (dmoz.org)   |\n    | and link back to that category using the {{dmoz}} template.         |\n    =========================({{NoMoreLinks}})=============================-->\n\n{{Formula One games}}\n\n{{Geoff Crammond Grand Prix}}\n\n[[Category:2002 video games]]\n[[Category:Cancelled Dreamcast games]]\n[[Category:Cancelled Xbox games]]\n[[Category:Infogrames games]]\n[[Category:Formula One video games]]\n[[Category:MicroProse games]]\n[[Category:Multiplayer and single-player video games]]\n[[Category:Racing simulators]]\n[[Category:Video games scored by James Hannigan]]\n[[Category:Video games developed in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Windows games]]\n[[Category:Windows-only games]]\n\n[[de:Grand Prix (Computerspiel)#Grand Prix 4]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox video game\n|title     = Grand Prix 4\n|image     = Grand Prix 4 Coverart.png\n|developer = [[MicroProse|MicroProse Chipping Sodbury]] \n|publisher = [[Atari, SA|Infogrames]]\n|designer  = [[Geoff Crammond]]\n|composer  = [[James Hannigan]]\n|engine    = \n|series    = \n|released  = {{vgrelease|PAL|June 21, 2002|NA|September 10, 2002}}\n|genre     = [[Sim racing|Racing simulation]]\n|modes     = [[Single-player video game|Single-player]], [[Multiplayer video game|Multiplayer]]\n|platforms = [[Microsoft Windows]]\n}}\n\n'''''Grand Prix 4''''', commonly known as '''''GP4''''', was released for the PC on June 21, 2002, is currently the last [[Formula One]] [[racing simulator]] released by the developer [[Geoff Crammond]] and the [[MicroProse]] label. Based on the [[2001 Formula One season]], GP4 essentially serves as a graphical and seasonal update of ''[[Grand Prix 3]]'' which had been released in 2000. The game retained the series' legendary [[physics engine]]. However it entered the market at a far less hospitable time than its three predecessors, and the game faced stiff competition from an alternative Formula One simulation from studios such as [[Image Space Incorporated|ISI]].\n\n== Modifications from version 3 ==\n\n{{Unreferenced section|date=March 2020}}\n''Grand Prix 4'' featured a heavily revised graphics [[Game engine|engine]] and updated physics including wet weather driving that even today is considered some of the best to ever feature in a motorsport simulation. Despite this, the game still showed Crammond's oft-commented dated approach to game design.\n\n* While it is possible to play the game on a [[Local area network|LAN]], [[multiplayer]] internet gameplay was not possible, due to licensing restrictions. Some individuals managed to circumvent this limitation later using the Free Tunngle Network.\n* The locked framerate and [[CPU]]-heavy graphics were still a big issue with the series despite a completely revised graphics engine. However, the graphics engine proved to be very scalable, supporting models and textures multiple times the detail of the original shipped materials.\n* The mod community faced similar frustrations with the track format and it took fully two years before the track format was truly \"cracked\". The first add-on tracks to be released for the game included [[Shanghai International Circuit|Shanghai]], [[Istanbul Park|Istanbul]] and [[Circuito de Jerez|Jerez]].\n* When the game was initially launched, it had a large number of [[Software bug|bugs]]. Many of these were addressed by a [[Patch (computing)|patch]] which was later included with the retail game, though the project was canned when Microprose closed and no further official fixes were forthcoming. To compensate for this some third party programmers addressed some of the remaining problems, and included enhancements which allowed the game to follow the updated rules of the Formula One championship.\n* Many claimed that the stated \"minimum requirements\" were set too low and that they could barely get the game to run on a significantly more powerful system.\n\nAlthough the game could be considered a relatively modest commercial success the chances of a further entry to the series could be considered slim to none because MicroProse's parent company [[Atari, SA|Infogrames]] dissolved the developer shortly after the game's release. Also, the [[Sony Interactive Entertainment|Sony Computer Entertainment]] brand's exclusive licensing deal for Formula One games rules out an update with official stats. An [[Xbox (console)|Xbox]] port of the title had been planned for release in late 2002 before being cancelled in October of that year.<ref>{{Cite magazine |title=In the chair with Geoff Crammond |magazine=[[Retro Gamer]] |publisher=[[Imagine Publishing]] |issue=69 |page=88}}</ref>\n\n== Reception ==\n{{Video game reviews\n| MC = 77/100<ref name=\"MC\">{{Cite web |title=Geoff Crammond's Grand Prix 4 for PC Reviews |url=https://www.metacritic.com/game/pc/geoff-crammonds-grand-prix-4 |website=[[Metacritic]] |publisher=[[CBS Interactive]] |accessdate=May 13, 2013}}</ref>\n| CGM = {{Rating|3|5}}<ref>{{Cite magazine |title=Grand Prix 4 |magazine=[[Computer Games Magazine]] |publisher=[[theGlobe.com]] |issue=146 |date=January 2003 |page=77}}</ref>\n| CGW = {{Rating|4.5|5}}<ref>{{Cite magazine |last=Smolka |first=Rob |title=Grand Prix 4 |url=http://www.cgwmuseum.org/galleries/issues/cgw_221.pdf |magazine=[[Computer Gaming World]] |publisher=[[Ziff Davis]] |issue=221 |date=December 2002 |page=124 |accessdate=February 16, 2019}}</ref>\n| EuroG = 10/10<ref>{{Cite web |last=Bramwell |first=Tom |date=July 7, 2002 |title=Grand Prix 4 |url=https://www.eurogamer.net/articles/r_gp4 |website=[[Eurogamer]] |publisher=Gamer Network |accessdate=February 16, 2019}}</ref>\n| GSpot = 8/10<ref>{{Cite web |last=Ajami |first=Amer |date=September 11, 2002 |title=Geoff Crammond's Grand Prix 4 Review [date mislabeled as \"September 12, 2002\"] |url=https://www.gamespot.com/reviews/geoff-crammonds-grand-prix-4-review/1900-2879976/ |website=[[GameSpot]] |publisher=CBS Interactive |accessdate=February 16, 2019}}</ref>\n| GSpy = {{Rating|4.5|5}}<ref>{{Cite web |last=Fryman |first=Avi |date=October 18, 2002 |title=GameSpy: Geoff Crammond's Grand Prix 4 |url=http://pc.gamespy.com/pc/grand-prix-4/543802p1.html |website=[[GameSpy]] |publisher=IGN Entertainment |accessdate=February 16, 2019}}</ref>\n| GameZone = 8.5/10<ref>{{Cite web |last=Lafferty |first=Michael |date=September 16, 2002 |title=Grand Prix 4 Review |url=http://pc.gamezone.com/gzreviews/r20314.htm |website=GameZone |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080125041007/http://pc.gamezone.com/gzreviews/r20314.htm |archivedate=January 25, 2008 |url-status=dead |accessdate=February 16, 2019}}</ref>\n| IGN = 8.3/10<ref>{{Cite web |last=Magruder |first=Randy |date=September 12, 2002 |title=Grand Prix 4 Review |url=https://www.ign.com/articles/2002/09/12/grand-prix-4-review |website=[[IGN]] |publisher=Ziff Davis |accessdate=February 16, 2019}}</ref>\n| JXV = 15/20<ref>{{Cite web |author=Jihem |date=June 21, 2002 |title=Test: Grand Prix 4 |url=http://www.jeuxvideo.com/articles/0000/00002214_test.htm |language=French |website=[[Jeuxvideo.com]] |publisher=Webedia |accessdate=February 16, 2019}}</ref>\n| PCGUS = 73%<ref>{{Cite magazine |last=Mahood |first=Andy |title=Grand Prix 4 |url=http://www.pcgamer.com/archives/2005/07/grand_prix_4.html |magazine=[[PC Gamer]] |publisher=[[Future US]] |volume=9 |issue=12 |date=December 2002 |page=98 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20060315132101/http://www.pcgamer.com/archives/2005/07/grand_prix_4.html |archivedate=March 15, 2006 |url-status=dead |accessdate=February 16, 2019}}</ref>\n| PCZone = 86%<ref>{{Cite web |last=Presley |first=Paul |date=August 5, 2002 |title=PC Review: Grand Prix 4 |url=http://www.computerandvideogames.com/article.php?id=77713 |website=[[PC Zone]] |publisher=[[Future plc]] |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070630230146/http://www.computerandvideogames.com/article.php?id=77713 |archivedate=June 30, 2007 |url-status=dead |accessdate=February 16, 2019}}</ref>\n}}\n\n''Grand Prix 4'' received \"generally favorable reviews\" according to the [[Review aggregator|review aggreation]] website [[Metacritic]].<ref name=\"MC\"/>\n\nThe game won the award in the Sports category at the [[British Academy of Film and Television Arts]] Awards in 2002.<ref>{{cite web |title=Interactive {{!}} Games - Sport in 2002 |url=http://awards.bafta.org/award/2002/interactive/games-sport |website=[[British Academy of Film and Television Arts]]}}</ref> It was also nominated for ''[[Computer Gaming World]]''{{'}}s 2002 \"Sports Game of the Year\" award, which ultimately went to ''[[Madden NFL 2003]]''. The editors called ''Grand Prix 4'' \"one of the better racing games in years past\".<ref>{{Cite magazine |author=CGW staff |title=Computer Gaming World's 2002 Games of the Year (Sports Game of the Year) |url=http://www.cgwmuseum.org/galleries/issues/cgw_225.pdf |magazine=Computer Gaming World |publisher=Ziff Davis |issue=225 |date=April 2003 |page=94 |accessdate=February 16, 2019}}</ref>\n\n{{clear}}\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{moby game|id=/windows/grand-prix-4}}\n*{{dmoz|Games/Video_Games/Driving_and_Racing/Simulations/Formula_1_Grand_Prix_Series/Grand_Prix_4|''Grand Prix 4''}}\n*[http://www.gp4central.com/ GP4 Central] - A fan site\n*[http://www.grandprixgames.org Grand Prix Games - The Community Place] - A fan forum\n*[http://gp4forever.com GP4 Forever] - A fan forum\n\n<!--==========================({{NoMoreLinks}})============================\n    | PLEASE BE CAUTIOUS IN ADDING MORE LINKS TO THIS ARTICLE. WIKIPEDIA  |\n    | IS NOT A COLLECTION OF LINKS NOR SHOULD IT BE USED FOR ADVERTISING. |\n    |                                                                     |\n    |           Excessive or inappropriate links WILL BE DELETED.         |\n    | See [[Wikipedia:External links]] & [[Wikipedia:Spam]] for details.  |\n    |                                                                     |\n    | If there are already plentiful links, please propose additions or   |\n    | replacements on this article's discussion page. Or submit your link |\n    | to the relevant category at the Open Directory Project (dmoz.org)   |\n    | and link back to that category using the {{dmoz}} template.         |\n    =========================({{NoMoreLinks}})=============================-->\n\n{{Formula One games}}\n\n{{Geoff Crammond Grand Prix}}\n\n[[Category:2002 video games]]\n[[Category:Cancelled Dreamcast games]]\n[[Category:Cancelled Xbox games]]\n[[Category:Infogrames games]]\n[[Category:Formula One video games]]\n[[Category:MicroProse games]]\n[[Category:Multiplayer and single-player video games]]\n[[Category:Racing simulators]]\n[[Category:Video games scored by James Hannigan]]\n[[Category:Video games developed in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Windows games]]\n[[Category:Windows-only games]]\n\n[[de:Grand Prix (Computerspiel)#Grand Prix 4]]\n", "name_user": "Mika1h", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Grand_Prix_4"}
{"title_page": "Danton (1983 film)", "text_new": "{{Infobox film\n| name           = Danton\n| image          = DantonPoster.jpg\n| caption        = Film poster\n| director       = [[Andrzej Wajda]]\n| producer       = [[Margaret M\u00e9n\u00e9goz]]<br />Barbara Pec-Slesicka\n| writer         = [[Jean-Claude Carri\u00e8re]]<br />collaboration with<br>[[Andrzej Wajda]]<br>[[Agnieszka Holland]]<br>Boles\u0142aw Micha\u0142ek<br>Jacek G\u0105siorowski \n| narrator       = \n| starring       = [[G\u00e9rard Depardieu]]\n| music          = [[Jean Prodromid\u00e8s]]\n| cinematography = Igor Luther\n| editing        = Halina Prugar-Ketling\n| distributor    = [[Gaumont Film Company|Gaumont]]\n| released       = {{Film date|df=y|1983|1|12|France|1983|1|31|Poland}}\n| runtime        = 136 minutes\n| country        = France<br />Poland<br />[[West Germany|West&nbsp;Germany]]\n| language       = French\n| budget         = \n| gross          = $10.4 million<ref name=\"auto\">{{cite web|url=http://www.jpbox-office.com/fichfilm.php?id=7057|title=Danton (1983) - JPBox-Office|first=|last=JP|website=www.jpbox-office.com}}</ref>\n}}\n'''''Danton''''' ({{IPA-fr|d\u0251\u0303t\u0254\u0303}}) is a 1983 [[French language]] film depicting the last weeks of [[Georges Danton]], one of the leaders of the [[French Revolution]]. It is an adaptation of the play ''[[The Danton Case]]'' by [[Stanis\u0142awa Przybyszewska]].\n\nThe film stars [[G\u00e9rard Depardieu]] in the title role, with [[Wojciech Pszoniak]] as [[Maximilien Robespierre]], and [[Patrice Ch\u00e9reau]] as [[Camille Desmoulins]]. It was directed by the Polish director [[Andrzej Wajda]] and was an [[international co-production]] between companies in [[France]], [[Poland]] and [[West Germany]]. All supporters of Danton (with the exception of Bourdon, who would later betray him) are played by French actors, while Robespierre's allies are played by Poles. \n\nNot always rigidly historical, the film draws continual parallels between the [[Reign of Terror]] during the French Revolution and the situation in contemporary Poland, in which the [[Solidarity (Polish trade union)|Solidarity]] movement was struggling against the oppression of the [[Soviet Union|Soviet]]-backed Polish government.<ref>Liner notes on the [[Criterion Collection]] DVD of the film.</ref><ref>\n[https://www.nytimes.com/movie/review?res=9804E0DC1F38F93BA1575AC0A965948260 WAJDA'S 'DANTON,' INSIDE THE FRENCH REVOLUTION By VINCENT CANBY], The New York Times, September 28, 1983 :\"In an interview in Le Monde, Mr. Wajda denies all associations between 18th-century France and 20th-century Poland\"</ref> The film had 1,392,779 admissions in France.<ref name=\"auto\"/>\n\n== Plot ==\nThe film begins in Paris in the cold spring of 1794 when the Reign of Terror is in full swing, with vehicles entering the city being searched and long lines of citizens grumbling in the rain as they wait to buy scarce bread. Ill in his flat, Robespierre sees Danton in the street, just returned from the country and being acclaimed by the hungry and dispirited people as their hero. \n\nWhen H\u00e9ron, head of the secret police, calls round, Robespierre instructs him to destroy the print shop of Desmoulins, who is publishing pro-Danton circulars. While Robespierre is being tended by his barber, his friend Saint-Just comes in and urges him to have Danton guillotined. He ignores him and goes to a meeting of the [[Committee of Public Safety]], the effective government of France, where other members also push for the elimination of Danton. Robespierre resists, because Danton is so popular with the ordinary people and is his friend. \n\nBefore that day's sitting of the [[National Convention]], the legislative assembly of the country, General Westermann discusses with Danton a coup to overthrow the tyranny of Robespierre and the Committee. Danton disapproves, even though friends warn him that Robespierre is planning to have him jailed and he should strike first. Danton is positive that the influence of his newspaper, [[Le Vieux Cordelier]], and the support of the people will keep him safe. However, he asks his supporter Bourdon to denounce H\u00e9ron and his secret police in the Convention, which leads to H\u00e9ron's arrest.\n\nThat night, Danton asks Robespierre to an elaborate dinner in a private room of a restaurant, fortifying himself in advance with copious wine. Robespierre refuses to eat and insists on a serious talk. He asks Danton to join his cause and stop fighting him, because he does not want to be forced to have Danton executed. Danton simply carries on drinking and refuses all Robespierre\u2019s advances. After Robespierre has left in disgust, in the street Danton meets a group of armed men who turn out to be part of Westermann's preparations for a coup. Once again, Danton refuses to join their illegal venture. \n\nRobespierre, having failed with Danton, then goes to the house of Desmoulins, who is furious that his printing business has been destroyed and refuses to talk to him. Robespierre tries to convince him that Danton is exploiting him, but is ignored. Desmoulins' wife begs Robespierre to stay and talk sense into her husband, because she wants him to live, but Robespierre can achieve nothing. He goes to the Committee of Public Safety and orders a warrant for the arrest that night of Danton, Desmoulins, Westermann and several of their associates. Though Danton could still rally support, he does not want to cause more bloodshed and accepts arrest, claiming that his oratory and the affection of the people will protect him.\n\nAt the National Convention in the  morning, members are outraged at the arrests, but Robespierre simply justifies his action by stating that Danton is an enemy of the Republic and must be tried regardless of his popularity. Having escaped arrest, Bourdon hastily changes sides and backs Robespierre. When the trial opens before the [[Revolutionary Tribunal]], only seven jurors can be found who will agree to vote Danton guilty but it continues regardless. Danton keeps breaking order to address the spectators, and the prosecutor Fouquier is unhappy because he has insufficient grounds for a conviction. Back in prison that night, Danton's confidence is shaken when another prisoner tells him how overjoyed he is to hear that Danton, the first president of the Committee and the creator of the Revolutionary Tribunal, is to be executed. \n\nNext day, while visiting the studio of the painter David, Robespierre is told by Fouquier that Danton's constant interruptions are making a farce of the trial, which lacks validity anyhow. Robespierre gets the Committee to issue a decree that anyone who speaks out of turn will be removed from court. Within minutes, all the accused have been bundled out and the verdict of guilty is read.\n\nOn the day before their execution Danton is depressed, not because of his death but because he feels that he has failed the people. Once the condemned men have been taken through the silent crowds to the scaffold and guillotined, Robespierre's long-maintained tension breaks and he relapses into shock. The noble ideals of the Revolution in the [[Declaration of the Rights of Man and of the Citizen]], recited to him by a child forced to learn it by heart, are fatally compromised.\n\n== Principal cast ==\n* [[G\u00e9rard Depardieu]] as [[Georges Danton]]\n* [[Wojciech Pszoniak]] as [[Maximilien Robespierre]]\n* [[Patrice Ch\u00e9reau]] as [[Camille Desmoulins]]\n* [[Bogus\u0142aw Linda]] as [[Louis de Saint-Just]]\n* [[Angela Winkler]] as [[Lucile Duplessis|Lucile Desmoulins]]\n* [[Andrzej Seweryn]] as [[Fran\u00e7ois Louis Bourdon]]\n* [[Serge Merlin]] as [[Pierre Philippeaux]]\n* [[Roland Blanche]] as [[Jean-Fran\u00e7ois Delacroix]]\n* [[Jacques Villeret]] as [[Fran\u00e7ois Joseph Westermann]]\n* [[Anne Alvaro]] as [[\u00c9l\u00e9onore Duplay]]\n* [[Roger Planchon]] as [[Antoine Quentin Fouquier-Tinville]]\n* [[Franciszek Starowieyski]] as [[Jacques-Louis David]]\n* Alain Mac\u00e9 as Fran\u00e7ois H\u00e9ron\n\n==Reception==\nThe film had been sponsored by France's first socialist government for decades, in anticipation of the bicentenary of the Revolution in 1989. Before its release, a private showing to the President of the Republic, [[Fran\u00e7ois Mitterrand]], and the Minister of Culture, [[Jack Lang (French politician)|Jack Lang]], evoked a frosty reaction. They had not expected such a cynical tale of power politics, show trials and cold-blooded judicial murder, familiar though it all was in [[Eastern Bloc|Eastern Europe]] under Soviet control.<ref>{{cite|first = Philippe|last = d'Hugues|article = Danton remis en cause par Andrzej Wajda |title = La Nouvelle Revue d'histoire|volume = 89|date = March 2017|page = 61}}</ref><ref>{{cite|first = Laurent |last = Dandrieu |title =  Dictionnaire passionn\u00e9 du cin\u00e9ma |publisher = L'Homme Nouveau |year = 2013|page = 76}}</ref> \n\n==Awards==\n* Prix Louis-Delluc 1982: Andrzej Wajda\n* C\u00e9sar 1983, Best director: Andrzej Wajda\n* BAFTA  Awards 1983, [[BAFTA Award for Best Film Not in the English Language|Best Foreign Language Film]]: Danton\n* Montr\u00e9al World Film Festival 1983, Best Actor: G\u00e9rard Depardieu & Wojciech Pszoniak\n* National Society of Film Critics Awards, USA 1983, Best Actor: G\u00e9rard Depardieu\n* Polish Film Festival 1984: Andrzej Wajda\n* London Critics Circle Film Awards 1984, Director of the Year: Andrzej Wajda\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Allmovie title|12215}}\n* {{IMDb title|0083789}}\n* 1983 review by Vincent Canby at [https://movies.nytimes.com/movie/review?res=9804E0DC1F38F93BA1575AC0A965948260  nytimes.com]\n*[https://www.criterion.com/current/posts/1072-danton-the-worst-of-times ''Danton: The Worst of Times''] an essay by Leonard Quart at the [[Criterion Collection]]\n\n{{Andrzej Wajda}}\n{{BAFTA Best Foreign Language Film}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Danton 1983}}\n[[Category:1983 films]]\n[[Category:1980s biographical films]]\n[[Category:1980s historical films]]\n[[Category:French films]]\n[[Category:French historical films]]\n[[Category:Polish films]]\n[[Category:French-language films]]\n[[Category:Biographical films about Georges Danton]]\n[[Category:Cultural depictions of Georges Danton]]\n[[Category:Cultural depictions of Maximilien Robespierre]]\n[[Category:Political drama films]]\n[[Category:French films based on plays]]\n[[Category:Films directed by Andrzej Wajda]]\n[[Category:Best Foreign Language Film BAFTA Award winners]]\n[[Category:Films whose director won the Best Director C\u00e9sar Award]]\n[[Category:Louis Delluc Prize winners]]\n[[Category:Films with screenplays by Jean-Claude Carri\u00e8re]]\n[[Category:French Revolution films]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox film\n| name           = Danton\n| image          = DantonPoster.jpg\n| caption        = Film poster\n| director       = [[Andrzej Wajda]]\n| producer       = [[Margaret M\u00e9n\u00e9goz]]<br />Barbara Pec-Slesicka\n| writer         = [[Jean-Claude Carri\u00e8re]]<br />collaboration with<br>[[Andrzej Wajda]]<br>[[Agnieszka Holland]]<br>Boles\u0142aw Micha\u0142ek<br>Jacek G\u0105siorowski \n| narrator       = \n| starring       = [[G\u00e9rard Depardieu]]\n| music          = [[Jean Prodromid\u00e8s]]\n| cinematography = Igor Luther\n| editing        = Halina Prugar-Ketling\n| distributor    = [[Gaumont Film Company|Gaumont]]\n| released       = {{Film date|df=y|1983|1|12|France|1983|1|31|Poland}}\n| runtime        = 136 minutes\n| country        = France<br />Poland<br />[[West Germany|West&nbsp;Germany]]\n| language       = French\n| budget         = \n| gross          = $10.4 million<ref name=\"auto\">{{cite web|url=http://www.jpbox-office.com/fichfilm.php?id=7057|title=Danton (1983) - JPBox-Office|first=|last=JP|website=www.jpbox-office.com}}</ref>\n}}\n'''''Danton''''' ({{IPA-fr|d\u0251\u0303t\u0254\u0303}}) is a 1983 [[French language]] film depicting the last weeks of [[Georges Danton]], one of the leaders of the [[French Revolution]]. It is an adaptation of the play ''[[The Danton Case]]'' by [[Stanis\u0142awa Przybyszewska]].\n\nThe film stars [[G\u00e9rard Depardieu]] in the title role, with [[Wojciech Pszoniak]] as [[Maximilien Robespierre]], and [[Patrice Ch\u00e9reau]] as [[Camille Desmoulins]]. It was directed by the Polish director [[Andrzej Wajda]] and was an [[international co-production]] between companies in [[France]], [[Poland]] and [[West Germany]]. All supporters of Danton (with the exception of Bourdon, who would later betray him) are played by French actors, while Robespierre's allies are played by Poles. \n\nNot always rigidly historical, the film draws continual parallels between the [[Reign of Terror]] during the French Revolution and the situation in contemporary Poland, in which the [[Solidarity (Polish trade union)|Solidarity]] movement was struggling against the oppression of the [[Soviet Union|Soviet]]-backed Polish government.<ref>Liner notes on the [[Criterion Collection]] DVD of the film.</ref><ref>\n[https://www.nytimes.com/movie/review?res=9804E0DC1F38F93BA1575AC0A965948260 WAJDA'S 'DANTON,' INSIDE THE FRENCH REVOLUTION By VINCENT CANBY], The New York Times, September 28, 1983 :\"In an interview in Le Monde, Mr. Wajda denies all associations between 18th-century France and 20th-century Poland\"</ref> The film had 1,392,779 admissions in France.<ref name=\"auto\"/>\n\n== Plot ==\nThe film begins in Paris in the cold spring of 1794 when the Reign of Terror is in full swing, with vehicles entering the city being searched and long lines of citizens grumbling in the rain as they wait to buy scarce bread. Ill in his flat, Robespierre sees Danton in the street, just returned from the country and being acclaimed by the hungry and dispirited people as their hero. \n\nWhen H\u00e9ron, head of the secret police, calls round, Robespierre instructs him to destroy the print shop of Desmoulins, who is publishing pro-Danton circulars. While Robespierre is being tended by his barber, his friend Saint-Just comes in and urges him to have Danton guillotined. He ignores him and goes to a meeting of the [[Committee of Public Safety]], the effective government of France, where other members also push for the elimination of Danton. Robespierre resists, because Danton is so popular with the ordinary people and is his friend. \n\nBefore that day's sitting of the [[National Convention]], the legislative assembly of the country, General Westermann discusses with Danton a coup to overthrow the tyranny of Robespierre and the Committee. Danton disapproves, even though friends warn him that Robespierre is planning to have him jailed and he should strike first. Danton is positive that the influence of his newspaper, [[Le Vieux Cordelier]], and the support of the people will keep him safe. However, he asks his supporter Bourdon to denounce H\u00e9ron and his secret police in the Convention, which leads to H\u00e9ron's arrest.\n\nThat night, Danton asks Robespierre to an elaborate dinner in a private room of a restaurant, fortifying himself in advance with copious wine. Robespierre refuses to eat and insists on a serious talk. He asks Danton to join his cause and stop fighting him, because he does not want to be forced to have Danton executed. Danton simply carries on drinking and refuses all Robespierre\u2019s advances. After Robespierre has left in disgust, in the street Danton meets a group of armed men who turn out to be part of Westermann's preparations for a coup. Once again, Danton refuses to join their illegal venture. \n\nRobespierre, having failed with Danton, then goes to the house of Desmoulins, who is furious that his printing business has been destroyed and refuses to talk to him. Robespierre tries to convince him that Danton is exploiting him, but is ignored. Desmoulins' wife begs Robespierre to stay and talk sense into her husband, because she wants him to live, but Robespierre can achieve nothing. He goes to the Committee of Public Safety and orders a warrant for the arrest that night of Danton, Desmoulins, Westermann and several of their associates. Though Danton could still rally support, he does not want to cause more bloodshed and accepts arrest, claiming that his oratory and the affection of the people will protect him.\n\nAt the National Convention in the  morning, members are outraged at the arrests, but Robespierre simply justifies his action by stating that Danton is an enemy of the Republic and must be tried regardless of his popularity. Having escaped arrest, Bourdon hastily changes sides and backs Robespierre. When the trial opens before the [[Revolutionary Tribunal]], only seven jurors can be found who will agree to vote Danton guilty but it continues regardless. Danton keeps breaking order to address the spectators, and the prosecutor Fouquier is unhappy because he has insufficient grounds for a conviction. Back in prison that night, Danton's confidence is shaken when another prisoner tells him how overjoyed he is to hear that Danton, the first president of the Committee and the creator of the Revolutionary Tribunal, is to be executed. \n\nNext day, while visiting the studio of the painter David, Robespierre is told by Fouquier that Danton's constant interruptions are making a farce of the trial, which lacks validity anyhow. Robespierre gets the Committee to issue a decree that anyone who speaks out of turn will be removed from court. Within minutes, all the accused have been bundled out and the verdict of guilty is read.\n\nOn the day before their execution Danton is depressed, not because of his death but because he feels that he has failed the people. Once the condemned men have been taken through the silent crowds to the scaffold and guillotined, Robespierre's long-maintained tension breaks and he relapses into shock. The noble ideals of the Revolution in the [[Declaration of the Rights of Man and of the Citizen]], recited to him by a child forced to learn it by heart, are fatally compromised.\n\n== Principal cast ==\n* [[G\u00e9rard Depardieu]] as [[Georges Danton]]\n* [[Wojciech Pszoniak]] as [[Maximilien Robespierre]]\n* [[Patrice Ch\u00e9reau]] as [[Camille Desmoulins]]\n* [[Bogus\u0142aw Linda]] as [[Louis de Saint-Just]]\n* [[Angela Winkler]] as [[Lucile Duplessis|Lucile Desmoulins]]\n* [[Andrzej Seweryn]] as [[Fran\u00e7ois Louis Bourdon]]\n* [[Serge Merlin]] as [[Pierre Philippeaux]]\n* [[Roland Blanche]] as [[Jean-Fran\u00e7ois Delacroix]]\n* [[Jacques Villeret]] as [[Fran\u00e7ois Joseph Westermann]]\n* [[Anne Alvaro]] as [[\u00c9l\u00e9onore Duplay]]\n* [[Roger Planchon]] as [[Antoine Quentin Fouquier-Tinville]]\n* [[Franciszek Starowieyski]] as [[Jacques-Louis David]]\n* Alain Mac\u00e9 as Fran\u00e7ois H\u00e9ron\n\n==Reception==\nThe film had been sponsored by France's first socialist government for decades, in anticipation of the bicentenary of the Revolution in 1989. Before its release, a private showing to the President of the Republic, [[Fran\u00e7ois Mitterrand]], and the Minister of Culture, [[Jack Lang (French politician)|Jack Lang]], evoked a frosty reaction. They had not expected such a cynical tale of power politics, show trials and cold-blooded judicial murder, familiar though it all was in [[Eastern Bloc|Eastern Europe]] under Soviet control.<ref>{{cite|first = Philippe|last = d'Hugues|article = Danton remis en cause par Andrzej Wajda |title = La Nouvelle Revue d'histoire|volume = 89|date = March 2017|page = 61}}</ref><ref>{{cite|first = Laurent |last = Dandrieu |title =  Dictionnaire passionn\u00e9 du cin\u00e9ma |publisher = L'Homme Nouveau |year = 2013|page = 76}}</ref> \n\n==Awards==\n* Prix Louis-Delluc 1982: Andrzej Wajda\n* C\u00e9sar 1983, Best director: Andrzej Wajda\n* BAFTA  Awards 1983, [[BAFTA Award for Best Film Not in the English Language|Best Foreign Language Film]]: Danton\n* Montr\u00e9al World Film Festival 1983, Best Actor: G\u00e9rard Depardieu & Wojciech Pszoniak\n* National Society of Film Critics Awards, USA 1983, Best Actor: G\u00e9rard Depardieu\n* Polish Film Festival 1984: Andrzej Wajda\n* London Critics Circle Film Awards 1984, Director of the Year: Andrzej Wajda\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Allmovie title|12215}}\n* {{IMDb title|0083789}}\n* 1983 review by Vincent Canby at [https://movies.nytimes.com/movie/review?res=9804E0DC1F38F93BA1575AC0A965948260  nytimes.com]\n*[https://www.criterion.com/current/posts/1072-danton-the-worst-of-times ''Danton: The Worst of Times''] an essay by Leonard Quart at the [[Criterion Collection]]\n\n{{Andrzej Wajda}}\n{{BAFTA Best Foreign Language Film}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Danton 1983}}\n[[Category:1983 films]]\n[[Category:1980s biographical films]]\n[[Category:1980s historical films]]\n[[Category:French films]]\n[[Category:French historical films]]\n[[Category:Polish films]]\n[[Category:French-language films]]\n[[Category:Biographical films about Georges Danton]]\n[[Category:Cultural depictions of Georges Danton]]\n[[Category:Cultural depictions of Maximilien Robespierre]]\n[[Category:Political drama films]]\n[[Category:French films based on plays]]\n[[Category:Films directed by Andrzej Wajda]]\n[[Category:Best Foreign Language Film BAFTA Award winners]]\n[[Category:Louis Delluc Prize winners]]\n[[Category:Films with screenplays by Jean-Claude Carri\u00e8re]]\n[[Category:French Revolution films]]\n", "name_user": "Diopic", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eExternal links:addCategory:Films whose director won the Best Director C\u00e9sar Award", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Danton_(1983_film)"}
{"title_page": "Dilsea carnosa", "text_new": "{{Speciesbox\n| image = Dilsea carnosa Crouan.jpg\n| image_caption =\n| genus = Dilsea\n| species = carnosa\n| authority = ([[Casimir Christoph Schmidel|Schmidel]]) [[Otto Kuntze|Kuntze]] (1898)\n| synonyms_ref =\n| synonyms =''Fucus carnosus'' <small>Schmidel (1794)</small><br/>\n''Fucus edulis'' <small>Stackhouse (1801)</small><br/>\n''Dilsea edulis'' <small>Stackhouse (1809)</small><br/>\n''Ulva edulis'' <small>(Stackhouse) [[Hans Christian Lyngbye|Lyngbye]] (1819)</small><br/>\n''Halymenia edulis'' <small>(Stackhouse) [[C.Agardh]] (1822)</small><br/>\n''Iridaea edulis'' <small>(Stackhouse) Bory de Saint-Vincent (1830)</small><br/>\n''Schizymenia edulis'' <small>(Stackhouse) Kleen (1874)</small><br/>\n''Sarcophyllis edulis'' <small>(Stackhouse) J.Agardh (1876)</small>\n}}\n[[File:Dilsea carnosa - Carantec.jpg|thumb|''Dilsea carnosa'', in [[Carantec]]]]\n\n'''''Dilsea carnosa''''', commonly known as the '''poor man's weather glass''' or the '''sea belt''', is a species of [[red algae]] in the [[Dumontiaceae]] family of the order [[Gigartinales]].\n\n==Taxonomy==\nThe species was first described scientifically by [[Casimir Christoph Schmidel|Schmidel]] in 1794, under the name ''Fucus carnosus''. The German botanist [[Otto Kuntze]] transferred the species to ''[[Dilsea]]'' in 1898.<ref name=Kuntze1898/>\n\n==Description==\nThis large alga is dark red, flattened and somewhat leathery. It may be 30&nbsp;cm or more long and 15&nbsp;cm wide. It is usually not branched but may split.<ref>Newton, L. 1931. ''A Handbook of the British Seaweeds''. British Museum, London</ref> It grows from a small discoid base.<ref name=\"Bunker\">Bunker, F.StP. D., Brodie, J.A., Maggs, C.A. and Bunker, Anne R. 2017. ''Seaweeds of Britain and Ireland.'' Second Edition, Wild Nature Press, Plymouth, UK. {{ISBN| 978-0-9955673-3-7}}</ref> The mature blade has a compact medulla enclosed within a cortex of rounded cells inwards and outwards of close radial filaments of about 6 cells.<ref name=\"Irvine\">Irvine, L.M.1983. ''Seaweeds of the British Isles''. Volume '''1''', Rhodophyta Part 2A. British Museum (Natural History) {{ISBN|0 565 00871 4}}</ref> It grows from a discoid [[holdfast]] with a short stipe.<ref>Dickinson, C.I. 1963. ''British Seaweeds'' The Kew Series</ref>\n\n==Habitat==\nAttached to rock in the lower littoral,<ref>Campbell, A.C. 1984. ''The Country Life Guide the Seashore and Shallow Seas of Britain and Europe.'' Country Life Books. {{ISBN|0 600 34396 0}}</ref> to a depth of 24 m or more.<ref name=\"Irvine\"/> It grows from a discoid holdfast with a short stipe.<ref>Dickinson, C.I. 1963. ''British Seaweeds'' The Kew Series</ref>\n\n==Reproduction==\nThe gametangial plants are dioecious, with male and female gametangia on separate plants. The spermatangia, male gametes, occur in patches near the edges of the fronds. [[Carpospore|Carposporangia]] release spores. Tetraspores occur near the margins and consist of four spores.<ref name=\"Irvine\"/>\n\n==Distribution==\nGenerally distributed around the [[British Isles]] including the [[Shetland Isles]] and [[Isle of Man]]; from [[Portugal]] to Arctic Russia.<ref name=\"Irvine\"/><ref>Hardy, F.G and Guiry, M.D. 2003. ''A Check-list and Atlas of the Seaweeds of Britain and Ireland''. British Phycological Society.{{ISBN| 0-9527115-16}}</ref>\n\n==Further reading==\nBunker, F.StP.D., Maggs, C.A., Brodie, J.A. and Bunker, A.R. 2017. ''Seaweeds of Britain and Ireland'' Second Edition.{{ISBN|978-0-9955673-3-7}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|refs=\n\n<ref name=Kuntze1898>Kuntze, O. (1898). Revisio generum plantarum. Part 3 (3).  pp. 1-576. Leipzig, London, Milano, New York, Paris: Arthur Felix, Dulau & Co., U. Hoepli, Gust. A. Schechert, Charles Klincksierck.</ref>\n\n}}\n\n{{Taxonbar|from=Q5277048}}\n\n[[Category:Dumontiaceae]]\n[[Category:Plants described in 1794]]\n", "text_old": "{{Speciesbox\n| image = Dilsea carnosa Crouan.jpg\n| image_caption =\n| genus = Dilsea\n| species = carnosa\n| authority = ([[Casimir Christoph Schmidel|Schmidel]]) [[Otto Kuntze|Kuntze]] (1898)\n| synonyms_ref =\n| synonyms =''Fucus carnosus'' <small>Schmidel (1794)</small><br/>\n''Fucus edulis'' <small>Stackhouse (1801)</small><br/>\n''Dilsea edulis'' <small>Stackhouse (1809)</small><br/>\n''Ulva edulis'' <small>(Stackhouse) [[Hans Christian Lyngbye|Lyngbye]] (1819)</small><br/>\n''Halymenia edulis'' <small>(Stackhouse) [[C.Agardh]] (1822)</small><br/>\n''Iridaea edulis'' <small>(Stackhouse) Bory de Saint-Vincent (1830)</small><br/>\n''Schizymenia edulis'' <small>(Stackhouse) Kleen (1874)</small><br/>\n''Sarcophyllis edulis'' <small>(Stackhouse) J.Agardh (1876)</small>\n}}\n[[File:Dilsea carnosa - Carantec.jpg|thumb|''Dilsea carnosa'', in [[Carantec]]]]\n\n'''''Dilsea carnosa''''', commonly known as the '''poor man's weather glass''' or the '''sea belt''', is a species of [[red algae]] in the [[Dumontiaceae]] family of the order [[Gigartinales]].\n\n==Taxonomy==\nThe species was first described scientifically by [[Casimir Christoph Schmidel|Schmidel]] in 1794, under the name ''Fucus carnosus''. The German botanist [[Otto Kuntze]] transferred the species to ''[[Dilsea]]'' in 1898.<ref name=Kuntze1898/>\n\n==Description==\nThis large alga is dark red, flattened and somewhat leathery. It may be 30&nbsp;cm or more long and 15&nbsp;cm wide. It is usually not branched but may split.<ref>Newton, L. 1931. ''A Handbook of the British Seaweeds''. British Museum, London</ref> It grows from a small discoid base.<ref name=\"Bunker\">Bunker, F.StP. D., Brodie, J.A., Maggs, C.A. and Bunker, Anne R. 2017. ''Seaweeds of Britain and Ireland.'' Second Edition, Wild Nature Press, Plymouth, UK. {{ISBN| 978-0-9955673-3-7}}</ref> The mature blade has a compact medulla enclosed within a cortex of rounded cells inwards and outwards of close radial filaments of about 6 cells.<ref name=\"Irvine\">Irvine, L.M.1983. ''Seaweeds of the British Isles''. Volume '''1''', Rhodophyta Part 2A. British Museum (Natural History) {{ISBN|0 565 00871 4}}</ref> It grows from a discoid holdfast with a short stipe.<ref>Dickinson, C.I. 1963. ''British Seaweeds'' The Kew Series</ref>\n\n==Habitat==\nAttached to rock in the lower littoral,<ref>Campbell, A.C. 1984. ''The Country Life Guide the Seashore and Shallow Seas of Britain and Europe.'' Country Life Books. {{ISBN|0 600 34396 0}}</ref> to a depth of 24 m or more.<ref name=\"Irvine\"/> It grows from a discoid holdfast with a short stipe.<ref>Dickinson, C.I. 1963. ''British Seaweeds'' The Kew Series</ref>\n\n==Reproduction==\nThe gametangial plants are dioecious, with male and female gametangia on separate plants. The spermatangia, male gametes, occur in patches near the edges of the fronds. [[Carpospore|Carposporangia]] release spores. Tetraspores occur near the margins and consist of four spores.<ref name=\"Irvine\"/>\n\n==Distribution==\nGenerally distributed around the [[British Isles]] including the [[Shetland Isles]] and [[Isle of Man]]; from [[Portugal]] to Arctic Russia.<ref name=\"Irvine\"/><ref>Hardy, F.G and Guiry, M.D. 2003. ''A Check-list and Atlas of the Seaweeds of Britain and Ireland''. British Phycological Society.{{ISBN| 0-9527115-16}}</ref>\n\n==Further reading==\nBunker, F.StP.D., Maggs, C.A., Brodie, J.A. and Bunker, A.R. 2017. ''Seaweeds of Britain and Ireland'' Second Edition.{{ISBN|978-0-9955673-3-7}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|refs=\n\n<ref name=Kuntze1898>Kuntze, O. (1898). Revisio generum plantarum. Part 3 (3).  pp. 1-576. Leipzig, London, Milano, New York, Paris: Arthur Felix, Dulau & Co., U. Hoepli, Gust. A. Schechert, Charles Klincksierck.</ref>\n\n}}\n\n{{Taxonbar|from=Q5277048}}\n\n[[Category:Dumontiaceae]]\n[[Category:Plants described in 1794]]\n", "name_user": "Phycodrys", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dilsea_carnosa"}
{"title_page": "Walter Rose (footballer)", "text_new": "{{Other people||Walter Rose (disambiguation){{!}}Walter Rose}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n| name           = Walter Rose\n| fullname       = Walter Rose\n| image          = Fotothek df roe-neg 0006575 014 Portrait Walter Roses der Betriebssportgemeinsch.jpg\n| caption        = Rose in 1954\n| height         =\n| birth_date     = {{Birth date|df=yes|1912|11|5}}\n| birth_place    = [[Leipzig]], [[German Empire]]\n| death_date     = {{Death date and age|df=yes|1989|12|27|1912|11|5}}\n| death_place    = [[Leipzig]], [[East Germany]]\n| position       = [[Defender (association football)|Defender]]\n| youthyears1    = 1929\u20131930\n| youthclubs1    = FC Viktoria 06 Leutzsch\n| youthyears2    = 1930\u20131932\n| youthclubs2    = KG Rote Sporteinheit Leutzsch\n| years1         = 1932\u20131940\n| clubs1         = [[SpVgg Leipzig]]\n| caps1          =\n| goals1         =\n| years2         = 1940\u20131942\n| clubs2         = PSV Chemnitz\n| caps2          =\n| goals2         =\n| years3         = 1945\u20131949\n| clubs3         = [[SpVgg Leipzig|SG Lindenau-Hafen]]\n| caps3          =\n| goals3         =\n| years4         = 1949\u20131954\n| clubs4         = [[BSG Chemie Leipzig (1950)|Industrie/Chemie Leipzig]]\n| caps4          = 152\n| goals4         = 26\n| totalcaps      =\n| totalgoals     =\n| nationalyears1 = 1937\n| nationalteam1  = [[Germany national football team|Germany]]\n| nationalcaps1  = 1\n| nationalgoals1 = 0\n| manageryears1  = 1952\u20131953\n| managerclubs1  = [[BSG Chemie Leipzig (1950)|Chemie Leipzig]]\n}}\n'''Walter Rose''' (5 November 1912 \u2013 27 December 1989) was a German [[Association football|footballer]] and [[Manager (association football)|manager]] who played as a [[Defender (association football)|defender]] and made one appearance for the [[Germany national football team|Germany national team]].<ref name=\"WF\">{{WorldFootball.net}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\nRose earned his first and only cap for [[Germany national football team|Germany]] on 29 August 1937 in a [[1938 FIFA World Cup qualification Group 1|1938 World Cup qualification]] match against [[Estonia national football team|Estonia]]. The home match, which took place in [[K\u00f6nigsberg]], finished as a 4\u20131 win for Germany.<ref name=\"EUF\">{{cite web |url=https://eu-football.info/_player.php?id=18021 |title=Walter Rose |website=EU-Football.info |access-date=9 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nRose died on 27 December 1989 at the age of 77.<ref name=\"WF\"/> His grandson, [[Marco Rose]], was also a football and later a [[Manager (association football)|manager]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bundesliga.com/en/bundesliga/news/marco-rose-5-things-on-borussia-monchengladbachs-inbound-new-head-coach-3651 |title=Marco Rose: 5 things on Borussia M\u00f6nchengladbach's inbound new head coach |website=[[Bundesliga]] |publisher=[[Deutsche Fu\u00dfball Liga]] |date=11 April 2019 |access-date=9 April 2020 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200409205149/https://www.bundesliga.com/en/bundesliga/news/marco-rose-5-things-on-borussia-monchengladbachs-inbound-new-head-coach-3651 |archive-date=9 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Career statistics==\n\n===International===\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n|-\n!colspan=3|[[Germany national football team|Germany]]<ref name=\"EUF\"/>\n|-\n!Year!!Apps!!Goals\n|-\n|1937||1||0\n|-\n!Total!!1!!0\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n'''General references'''\n* {{cite book |title=Fu\u00dfball in Berlin, der deutschen Ostzone und DDR 1945\u201350 |trans-title=Football in Berlin, the German Eastern Zone and GDR 1945\u201350 |language=de |publisher=[[International Federation of Football History & Statistics]]}}\n* {{cite magazine |title=Libero: Deutsche Fu\u00dfballzeitschrift |date=April\u2013July 1988 |number=1 |language=de |publisher=[[International Federation of Football History & Statistics]]}}\n* {{cite book |last1=Horn |first1=Michael |last2=Weise |first2=Gottfried |title=Das gro\u00dfe Lexikon des DDR-Fu\u00dfballs |trans-title=The great lexicon of GDR football |date=1 April 2004 |language=de |location=Berlin |publisher=Schwarzkopf & Schwarzkopf |isbn=3-89602-536-8}}\n* {{cite book |last=Gr\u00fcne |first=Hardy |title=Enzyklop\u00e4die des deutschen Ligafu\u00dfballs |trans-title=Encyclopedia of German football leagues |volume=Band 1: Vom Kronprinzen bis zur Bundesliga. 1890 bis 1963. Deutsche Meisterschaft, Gauliga, Oberliga. Zahlen, Bilder, Geschichten. [Volume 1: From the Kronprinz to the Bundesliga. 1890 to 1963. German championship, Gauliga, Oberliga. Numbers, pictures, stories.] |year=1996 |language=de |location=Kassel |publisher=Agon Sportverlag |isbn=3-928562-85-1}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{DFB|type=player|name=Walter Rose player profile}}\n* {{DFB|type=coach|name=Walter Rose manager profile}}\n* {{Kicker}}\n* {{Fussballdaten}}\n* {{NFT player}}\n* {{FootballDatabase.eu}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Rose, Walter}}\n[[Category:1912 births]]\n[[Category:1989 deaths]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Leipzig]]\n[[Category:Footballers from Saxony]]\n[[Category:German footballers]]\n[[Category:East German footballers]]\n[[Category:Germany international footballers]]\n[[Category:Association football defenders]]\n[[Category:SpVgg Leipzig players]]\n[[Category:BSG Chemie Leipzig (1950) players]]\n[[Category:DDR-Oberliga players]]\n[[Category:East German football managers]]\n[[Category:BSG Chemie Leipzig (1950) managers]]\n[[Category:DDR-Oberliga managers]]\n\n\n{{Germany-footy-bio-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Other people||Walter Rose (disambiguation){{!}}Walter Rose}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n| name           = Walter Rose\n| fullname       = Walter Rose\n| image          = Fotothek df roe-neg 0006575 014 Portrait Walter Roses der Betriebssportgemeinsch.jpg\n| caption        = Rose in 1954\n| height         =\n| birth_date     = {{Birth date|df=yes|1912|11|5}}\n| birth_place    = [[Leipzig]], [[German Empire]]\n| death_date     = {{Death date and age|df=yes|1989|12|27|1912|11|5}}\n| death_place    = [[Leipzig]], [[East Germany]]\n| position       = [[Defender (association football)|Defender]]\n| youthyears1    = 1929\u20131930\n| youthclubs1    = FC Viktoria 06 Leutzsch\n| youthyears2    = 1930\u20131932\n| youthclubs2    = KG Rote Sporteinheit Leutzsch\n| years1         = 1932\u20131940\n| clubs1         = [[SpVgg Leipzig]]\n| caps1          =\n| goals1         =\n| years2         = 1940\u20131942\n| clubs2         = PSV Chemnitz\n| caps2          =\n| goals2         =\n| years3         = 1945\u20131949\n| clubs3         = [[SpVgg Leipzig|SG Lindenau-Hafen]]\n| caps3          =\n| goals3         =\n| years4         = 1949\u20131954\n| clubs4         = [[BSG Chemie Leipzig (1950)|Industrie/Chemie Leipzig]]\n| caps4          = 152\n| goals4         = 26\n| totalcaps      =\n| totalgoals     =\n| nationalyears1 = 1937\n| nationalteam1  = [[Germany national football team|Germany]]\n| nationalcaps1  = 1\n| nationalgoals1 = 0\n| manageryears1  = 1952\u20131953\n| managerclubs1  = [[BSG Chemie Leipzig (1950)|Chemie Leipzig]]\n}}\n'''Walter Rose''' (5 November 1912 \u2013 27 December 1989) was a German [[Association football|footballer]] and [[Manager (association football)|manager]] who played as a [[Defender (association football)|defender]] and made one appearance for the [[Germany national football team|Germany national team]].<ref name=\"WF\">{{WorldFootball.net}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\nRose earned his first and only cap for [[Germany national football team|Germany]] on 29 August 1937 in a [[1938 FIFA World Cup qualification Group 1|1938 World Cup qualification]] match against [[Estonia national football team|Estonia]]. The home match, which took place in [[K\u00f6nigsberg]], finished as a 4\u20131 win for Germany.<ref name=\"EUF\">{{cite web |url=https://eu-football.info/_player.php?id=18021 |title=Walter Rose |website=EU-Football.info |access-date=9 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nRose died on 27 December 1989 at the age of 77.<ref name=\"WF\"/> His grandson, [[Marco Rose]], was also a football and later a [[Manager (association football)|manager]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bundesliga.com/en/bundesliga/news/marco-rose-5-things-on-borussia-monchengladbachs-inbound-new-head-coach-3651 |title=Marco Rose: 5 things on Borussia M\u00f6nchengladbach's inbound new head coach |website=[[Bundesliga]] |publisher=[[Deutsche Fu\u00dfball Liga]] |date=11 April 2019 |access-date=9 April 2020 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200409205149/https://www.bundesliga.com/en/bundesliga/news/marco-rose-5-things-on-borussia-monchengladbachs-inbound-new-head-coach-3651 |archive-date=9 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Career statistics==\n\n===International===\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n|-\n!colspan=3|[[Germany national football team|Germany]]<ref name=\"EUF\"/>\n|-\n!Year!!Apps!!Goals\n|-\n|1937||1||0\n|-\n!Total!!1!!0\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n'''General references'''\n* {{cite book |title=Fu\u00dfball in Berlin, der deutschen Ostzone und DDR 1945\u201350 |trans-title=Football in Berlin, the German Eastern Zone and GDR 1945\u201350 |language=de |publisher=[[International Federation of Football History & Statistics]]}}\n* {{cite magazine |title=Libero: Deutsche Fu\u00dfballzeitschrift |date=April\u2013July 1988 |number=1 |language=de |publisher=[[International Federation of Football History & Statistics]]}}\n* {{cite book |last1=Horn |first1=Michael |last2=Weise |first2=Gottfried |title=Das gro\u00dfe Lexikon des DDR-Fu\u00dfballs |trans-title=The great lexicon of GDR football |date=1 April 2004 |language=de |location=Berlin |publisher=Schwarzkopf & Schwarzkopf |isbn=3-89602-536-8}}\n* {{cite book |last=Gr\u00fcne |first=Hardy |title=Enzyklop\u00e4die des deutschen Ligafu\u00dfballs |tra