vernment [[brainwashing|brainwashes]] one particular hoodlum into subservience.\n| <ref name=tropes/><ref name=rollingstonetop10/><ref>{{cite book|last=McDougal|first=Stuart Y.|title=Stanley Kubrick's A Clockwork Orange|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Uwj5qK-RUj0C&pg=PA1|date=7 July 2003|publisher=Cambridge University Press|isbn=978-0-521-57488-4}}</ref>\n|-\n| ''[[Cloud Atlas (film)|Cloud Atlas]]''\n| 2012\n| Adapted from the 2004 novel of the same name by David Mitchell. Set across six different eras (1849, 1936, 1973, 2012, 2144 and 2321), the movie tells the story a few group of souls crossing each other along different incarnations and how it changes the world according time passes.\n| <ref name=grimfuture/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://io9.com/5955079/is-cloud-atlas-an-unholy-mess-or-a-brilliant-masterpiece-yes|title=Is Cloud Atlas an unholy mess or a brilliant masterpiece? Yes.|first=Charlie Jane|last=Anders|date=26 October 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/daviddisalvo/2012/10/29/review-cloud-atlas-is-a-noble-disaster/|title=Review: 'Cloud Atlas' is a Noble Disaster|first=David|last=DiSalvo|date=29 October 2012}}</ref> <!-- http://www.slate.com/articles/arts/movies/2012/10/cloud_atlas_starring_tom_hanks_and_halle_berry_reviewed.html -->\n|-\n| ''[[Code 46]]''\n| 2003\n| A futuristic 'Brief Encounter', a love story in which the romance is doomed by genetic incompatibility.\n| <ref name=playlist/>\n|-\n| ''[[Colossus: The Forbin Project]]''\n| 1970\n| The film which is based upon [[Dennis Feltham Jones]]' science fiction novel ''[[Colossus (novel)|Colossus]]'' (1966), is about a massive American defense computer, named Colossus, after becoming [[Sentience|sentient]] logically follows its original directives to the dismay of its programmers by [[Cybernetic revolt|assuming control of the world]] and all human affairs for the good of mankind<ref>{{Tcmdb title|id=71253|title=Colossus: The Forbin Project}}</ref> during the [[Cold War]] threat of [[nuclear war]].<ref name=neolib/>\n| <ref name=neolib/><ref name=overlooked/><ref>{{cite web|last1=Wheeler Winston Dixon|first1=Ryan|title=Colossus \u2013 The Forbin Project \u2013 No Longer Sci-Fi|url=http://blog.unl.edu/dixon/2015/01/16/colossus-the-forbin-project-no-longer-sci-fi/|accessdate=9 September 2015|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://archive.is/20160124130740/http://blog.unl.edu/dixon/2015/01/16/colossus-the-forbin-project-no-longer-sci-fi/|archivedate=24 January 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last1=Westfahl|first1=Gary|title=The Greenwood Encyclopedia of Science Fiction and Fantasy: Themes, Works, and Wonders|date=2005|isbn=978-0313329500|page=482|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=3JXnz9x9sO4C&pg=PA482&lpg=PA482&dq=Colossus:+The+Forbin+Project+dystopia|accessdate=9 September 2015}}</ref>\n|-\n| ''[[The Congress (2013 film)|The Congress]]''\n| 2013\n| ''The Congress'' is a [[late capitalism|late-capitalist]] dystopia in which a corporate media behemoth \"Miramount\" has effectively usurped control of all human consciousness.<ref name=slateart/> In it an aging actress decides to [[Digital immortality|scan]] her body to sign over to Miramount Studios which allows the company to digitize every trait that she possesses and use it in any movie they choose. The hallucinogenic [[Films with live action and animation|live-action/animation]] film represents corporate interests taking advantage of the individual and was partly inspired by [[Stanis\u0142aw Lem]]'s novel ''[[The Futurological Congress]]''.\n| <ref name=slateart>{{cite web|last1=Stevens|first1=Dana|title=The Art House in Your Living Room|url=http://www.slate.com/articles/arts/movies/2014/08/the_congress_the_strange_little_cat_and_the_one_i_love_vod_film_reviews.html|accessdate=15 June 2015|date=8 August 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Barrett|first1=Michael|title=The Home Vidiot: January videos bring a dose of strangeness to awards season|url=http://www.sacurrent.com/sanantonio/the-home-vidiot-january-videos-bring-a-dose-of-strangeness-to-awards-season/Content?oid=2375458|accessdate=15 June 2015|date=21 January 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Glinter|first1=Ezra|title=The Revolution Will Be Animated|url=http://forward.com/culture/204755/the-revolution-will-be-animated/|accessdate=15 June 2015|date=28 August 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Pevere|first1=Geoff|title=The Congress: Toon tyranny or animated utopia?|url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/arts/film/film-reviews/the-congress-toon-tyranny-or-animated-utopia/article20248192/|newspaper=The Globe and Mail|accessdate=15 June 2015|date=29 August 2014}}</ref>\n|-\n| ''[[The Cybernetic Grandma]]''\n| 1962\n|  a 1962 Czechoslovakian stop motion puppet cartoon. It is a surreal science fiction-horror animation film, showing a dystopian situation where machines tend humans into a cybernetic lifestyle.\n| \n|-\n| ''[[Dark City (1998 film)|Dark City]]''\n| 1998\n| A man struggles with memories of his past, including a wife he cannot remember, in a nightmarish world with no sun and run by beings with telekinetic powers who seek the souls of humans.\n| <ref name=taste/><ref name=tropes/>\n|-\n| ''[[Dark Metropolis]]''\n| 2010\n| Mankind has lost a 300-year war against a genetically enhanced race that man created, abused and finally tortured. Now the descendants of that race - known as the 'Ghen' control the planet Earth from advanced underground cities.\n| <ref>{{cite web|first1=Michelle|last1=(Unknown)|title={ARC Review+Giveaway} Dark Metropolis by Jaclyn Dolamore|url=http://bookbriefs.net/2014/06/02/arc-reviewgiveaway-dark-metropolis-jaclyn-dolamore/|accessdate=13 June 2015|date=2 June 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Dark Metropolis|url=http://www.filmaffinity.com/en/film624359.html|publisher=[[FilmAffinity]]|accessdate=13 June 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Scheib|first1=Richard|title=Dark Metropolis|url=http://moria.co.nz/sciencefiction/dark-metropolis-2010.htm|accessdate=13 June 2015}}</ref>\n|-\n| ''[[Dawn of the Planet of the Apes]]''\n|2014\n|Ten years after the pandemic of the deadly [[Rise of the Planet of the Apes|ALZ-113 virus]], or Simian Flu, the worldwide human population has been drastically reduced, with only about one in five hundred genetically immune to the virus. Apes, with [[Genetic engineering|genetically]] [[Intelligence amplification|enhanced intelligence]] caused by the same virus, have started to build a civilization of their own. [[Caesar (Planet of the Apes)|Caesar]] is the [[Common chimpanzee|chimpanzee]] leader of an ape colony in the [[Muir Woods]] near San Francisco. Caesar's son Blue Eyes and his friend Ash encounter a man named Carver in the woods, who panics and shoots Ash, wounding him. Carver's party, led by Malcolm, arrive while a number of apes join Blue Eyes and Ash. Caesar orders the humans to leave, and they flee to their community in San Francisco, centered around \"the tower\", a partially finished skyscraper. Prompted by Koba, a scarred [[bonobo]] who holds a grudge against humans for experimental mistreatment. \n|<ref>{{Citation|last=Reeves|first=Matt|title=Dawn of the Planet of the Apes|date=11 July 2014|url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt2103281/|others=Gary Oldman, Keri Russell, Andy Serkis|accessdate=21 November 2017}}</ref>\n|-\n| ''[[The Day the Earth Caught Fire]]''\n| 1961\n| One of the classic apocalyptic films of its era, this film depicts the US and Russia unwittingly testing atomic bombs at the same time, altering the Earth's axis of rotation. \n| <ref name=gaze/>\n|-\n| ''[[Daybreakers]]''\n| 2009\n| In the year 2019, a plague has transformed almost every human into vampires. Faced with a dwindling blood supply, the fractured dominant race plots their survival.\n| <ref>{{cite news|last1=Pulver|first1=Andrew|title=Film review: Daybreakers|url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/2010/jan/07/daybreakers-review|newspaper=The Guardian|accessdate=13 June 2015|date=7 January 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite magazine|la