y|url=https://archive.org/stream/variety153-1944-01#page/n51/mode/2up|title=The Moon Is Down}}</ref>\n|-\n| ''[[Mortal Engines (film)|Mortal Engines]]''\n| 2018\n| In the future, the \"sixty-minute war\" led humanity to the brink of extinction. Digital and other modern technology was lost and now only 19th-century technology is used. Under the philosophy of Municipal Darwinism, massive engines were implanted to cities such as London to make then movable in order to hunt down any smaller settlements and consume their resources. Opponents of this way of life are stigmatized and wanted as criminals. Based on the 2001 novel by Philip Reeve.\n|\n|-\n| ''[[Natural City]]''\n| 2003\n| A colony world that integrates robots, androids and cyborgs amongst the population.\n| <ref>{{cite web|work=Variety|url=https://variety.com/2003/film/reviews/natural-city-1200538563/|title=Review: 'Natural City'|date=16 October 2013|last=Elley|first=Derek}}</ref>\n|-\n| ''[[Never Let Me Go (2010 film)|Never Let Me Go]]''\n| 2010\n| Based on [[Kazuo Ishiguro]]'s 2005 [[Never Let Me Go (novel)|novel of the same name]].\n| <ref name=tropes/><ref name=miami/>\n|-\n| ''[[Nightfall (1988 film)|Nightfall]]''\n| 1988\n| Based on [[Isaac Asimov]]'s 1941 [[Nightfall (Asimov novelette and novel)|story of the same name]]. In a distant planet with three suns where its inhabitants live in a perpetual daylight, two factions of the planet lead by rational scientist Aton and frantic religious Sor face each other when an incoming eclipse will cause the arrival of the night, threatening to collapse its civilization.\n| <ref>{{cite web|work=LA Times|date=26 September 1988|title=MOVIE REVIEW : \u2018Nightfall\u2019: A Classic Asimov Tale Gone Bad|url=https://www.latimes.com/archives/la-xpm-1988-09-26-ca-1728-story.html|first=Chris|last=Willman}}</ref>\n|-\n| ''[[Nineteen Eighty-Four (1984 film)|Nineteen Eighty-Four]]''\n| 1984\n| Based on [[George Orwell]]'s 1949 [[1984 (novel)|novel of the same name]].\n| <ref n