teland future to repair failed drones from Tet (a giant space station where humanity awaits to move Jupiter's moon Titan) after Earth was invaded by alien race that sixty years ago destroyed the Moon and caused several alterations in Earth's surface, who locates a hibernation capsule to find a woman inside it that she makes him doubt about the truth of the alien invasion.\n| <ref name=grimfuture/><ref>{{cite web|work=Review Journal|date=19 April 2013|title='Oblivion' a fun blast of sci-fi cinema, just as long as you don't over analyze its plot|url=http://www.reviewjournal.com/columns-blogs/entertainment/movies/oblivion-fun-blast-sci-fi-cinema-just-long-you-dont-overanalyze|last=Lawrence|first=Christopher}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title='Oblivion' review: a post-apocalyptic beauty that succeeds even while it stumbles|work=The Verge|url=https://www.theverge.com/2013/4/17/4232724/oblivion-review|last=Bishop|first=Bryan|date=17 April 2013}}</ref>\n|-\n| ''[[The Omega Man]]''\n| 1971\n| The second of three adaptations of [[Richard Matheson]]'s 1954 novel ''[[I Am Legend (novel)|I Am Legend]]''. In a world collapsed after a worldwide disease, Robert Neville is a scientist immune to the plague in permanent searching for a cure for the infected, turned in an religious cult of albino mutants named The Family and lead by demented Matthias, who is obsessed to destroy Neville and all trace of technology he believes blame of the world downfall.\n| <ref name=tropes/><ref name=gaze/>\n|-\n| ''[[On the Beach (1959 film)|On the Beach]]''\n| 1959\n| Based on [[Nevil Shute]]'s 1957 [[On the Beach (novel)|novel of the same name]] depicting the aftermath of a nuclear war.\n| <ref name=overlooked/>\n|-\n| ''[[Outland (film)|Outland]]''\n| 1981\n| Set on Jupiter's moon Io, it has been described as a space Western, and bears thematic resemblances to the classic 1952 film High Noon.\n| <ref name=show/>\n|-\n| ''[[Paranoia 1.0]]'' (originally ''One Point O'') \n| 2004\n| The film is a [[Kafkaesque]] nightmare in which a young computer programmer is an unwitting guinea pig in a corporate experiment to test a new advertising scheme.\n| <ref>{{cite web|title=Top 50 Dystopian Movies of All Time|url=http://snarkerati.com/movie-news/the-top-50-dystopian-movies-of-all-time/|publisher=Snarkerati (Web magazine)|accessdate=17 June 2015|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150204064750/http://snarkerati.com/movie-news/the-top-50-dystopian-movies-of-all-time/|archivedate=4 February 2015|date=28 September 2007}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Franco|first1=Ultimo|title=Paranoia 1.0 (2004)|url=http://www.dreadcentral.com/reviews/3604/paranoia-1-0-2004/|accessdate=17 June 2015|date=16 January 2005}}</ref>\n|-\n| ''[[Planet of the Apes#Original film series|Planet of the Apes]]'' (original series)\n| 1968\u20141973\n|  Most of humanity is extinguished in a thermonuclear war. In the course of the two following millennia, intelligent apes (chimpanzees, gorillas and orangutans) become the dominant kind and establish an organized society. During the 40th century, an ultra-powerful nuclear bomb is launched as a last resort in a conflict between mutant humans and gorillas, ultimately destroying the entire planet.\n| <ref name=playlist/><ref name=tropes/>\n|-\n| ''[[Planet of the Apes#Reboot series|Planet of the Apes]]'' (reboot series)\n| 2011\u2014present\n|  A colony of apes in a sanctuary is affected by a viral gas which enhances their intelligence. As a result, they flee the sanctuary and form an organized society apart from humans. Ten years later, that same virus causes a massive pandemic disease called the Simian flu, which ultimately wipes out all humans with the exception of those genetically immune to the virus. A group of immune human survivors form a colony and eventually engage in a war with the apes. \n| <ref name=grimfuture/><ref name=dawn>{{cite web|url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/movie/dawn-planet-apes/review/715555|work=Hollywood Reporter|title='Dawn of t