lso endorsed consumerism and technological dependency. \n| <ref name=jstor/><ref name=conservatives/>\n|-\n| ''[[Watchmen (film)|Watchmen]]''\n| 2009\n| Based on the 1986\u201387 DC Comics limited series of the same name by Alan Moore and Dave Gibbons, the film is set in an alternate history in the year 1985 at the height of the Cold War between the United States and the Soviet Union, as a group of mostly retired American superheroes investigates the murder of one of their own before uncovering an elaborate and deadly conspiracy.\n| <ref name=routledge>{{cite book|title=The Routledge Companion to Science Fiction|editor1=Bould, Mark|editor2=Butler, Andrew|editor3=Roberts, Adam|editor4=Vint, Sherryl|year=2009|publisher=Routledge|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=aD-PAgAAQBAJ|isbn=9781135228354}}</ref>\n|-\n| ''[[Waterworld]]''\n| 1995\n|  Massive ice caps have melted, and all of Earth's land became submersed. The few surviving humans, who live in big ships and artificial atolls, are poor and ignorant, since they have lost most of their resources, as well as their technological and historical knowledge. \n| <ref name=grimfuture/><ref name=hicks/><ref>{{cite web|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110310081346/http://www.film.com/movies/waterworld/story/married-movies-waterworld-two-disc/24155094|archivedate=10 March 2011|title=Married with Movies: Waterworld - Two-Disc Extended Edition|url=http://www.film.com/movies/waterworld/story/married-movies-waterworld-two-disc/24155094|last=Taylor|first=Dawn|date=6 November 2008|work=Film.com}}</ref>\n|-\n| ''[[Westworld (film)|Westworld]]''\n| 1973\n| Written and directed by [[Michael Crichton]]. A [[theme park]] focusing on the [[Old West]] goes haywire when the robots turn against the humans.\n| <ref name=avclub70s/>\n|-\n| ''[[What Happened to Monday]]''\n| 2017\n| Circa 2043 overpopulation has led to a strict one-child policy where all but a mother's eldest child are put into cryosleep.\n| <ref>{{cite web|last1=Richford|first1=Rhonda|title=Willem Dafoe Joins Glenn Close, Noomi Rapace in 'What Happened to Monday'|url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/willem-dafoe-joins-glenn-close-812369|website=Hollywood Reporter|accessdate=1 August 2015|date=31 July 2015|quote=The sci-fi thriller takes place in a not-so-distant future ravaged by overpopulation and famine and in which a one-child policy is in global effect. Seven sisters, each named after a day of the week, take on one identity to outwit Glenn Close's enforcer.}}</ref>\n|-\n| ''[[When Worlds Collide (1951 film)|When Worlds Collide]]''\n| 1951\n|  A rogue star hurtles towards Earth, imperiling life. Some escape to the star's planet on a space ark.\n| <ref name=gaze/>\n|-\n| ''[[World on a Wire]]''\n| 1973\n| German television movie (original title ''Welt am Draht''), directed by [[Rainer Werner Fassbinder]].\n| <ref name=overlooked/><ref>{{cite web|work=Criterion|url=http://www.criterion.com/current/posts/2152-world-on-a-wire-the-hall-of-mirrors|last=Halter|first=Ed|title=World on a Wire: The Hall of Mirrors|date=21 February 2012}}</ref>\n|-\n| ''[[X-Men: Days of Future Past]]''\n| 2014\n| The plot toggles between the political tumult of 1973 and a not-so-distant dystopian future. \n| <ref>{{cite web|work=Variety|url=https://variety.com/2014/film/reviews/film-review-x-men-days-of-future-past-1201177971/|title=Film Review: X-Men: Days of Future Past}}</ref>\n|-\n| ''[[Z for Zachariah (film)|Z for Zachariah]]'' \n|  2015 \n| Based on the book of the same name by Robert C. O'Brien published posthumously in 1974. In the wake of a disaster that wipes out most of civilization, two men and a young woman find themselves in an emotionally charged love triangle as the last known survivors.\n| <ref>{{Cite web|title = Z for Zachariah Takes a Thrilling, Intimate Approach to Dystopia|url = http://www.vulture.com/2015/08/movie-review-z-for-zachariah-does-dystopia-well.html|website = Vulture|accessdate = 28 September 2015}}</ref>\n|-\n| ''[[Z.P.G.]]''\n| 1972\n| Z.P.G. (short for \"Zero Population Growth\") is inspired by the non-fiction best-selling book The Population Bomb by Paul R. Ehrlich. The film concerns an overpopulated future Earth, whose world government executes those who violate a 30-year ban on having children.\n| <ref>{{cite web|work=Dead Channels: The San Francisco Festival of Fantastic Film|url=http://www.deadchannels.com/z_p_g.php|title=Z.P.G. (Zero Population Growth)|access-date=15 March 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170514052958/http://www.deadchannels.com/z_p_g.php|archive-date=14 May 2017|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n|-\n| ''[[Zardoz]]''\n| 1974\n| The post-apocalypse population is divided into the immortal, technologically advanced but depressive \"Eternals\" and mortal, food-supplying, often exterminated \"Brutals\".\n| <ref name=tropes/><ref name=gaze/><ref>{{cite web|work=Tor.com|title=Stay Inside My Aura: Why Zardoz is the Arty Dystopian Film You Can't Believe Exists|url=http://www.tor.com/blogs/2011/04/stay-inside-my-aura-why-zardoz-is-the-arty-dystopian-film-you-cant-believe-exists|last=Britt|first=Ryan|date=11 April 2011}}</ref>\n|-\n| ''[[The Zero Theorem]]''\n| 2013\n| Centres on a reclusive computer genius working on a formula to determine whether life holds any meaning.\n| <ref name=zero>{{cite web|title=Terry Gilliam on His Epic New Dystopian Film The Zero Theorem|work=Wired|url=https://www.wired.com/2014/09/zero-theorem/|last=Moore|first=Bo|date=18 September 2014}}</ref> \n|-\n|}\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of dystopian literature]]\n* [[List of dystopian comics]]\n* [[List of dystopian music, TV programs, and games]]\n* List of [[List of biopunk works|biopunk]] and [[List of cyberpunk works|cyberpunk]] works\n* [[Apocalyptic and post-apocalyptic fiction]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n{{Film genres}}\n\n[[Category:Dystopian films| ]]\n[[Category:Lists of speculative fiction films|Dystopian films]]\n[[Category:Lists of films by genre|Dystopian films]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Wikipedia list article}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2019}}\n{{distinguish|List of apocalyptic and post-apocalyptic fiction}}\nThis is a '''list of dystopian films'''. A [[dystopia]] (from the Greek \u03b4\u03c5\u03c3- and \u03c4\u03cc\u03c0\u03bf\u03c2, alternatively, '''cacotopia''',<ref name=\"Bentham\">\nCacotopia (\u03ba\u03b1\u03ba\u03cc, caco = bad) was the term used by [[Jeremy Bentham]] in his 19th century works ({{cite web|url=http://www.netcharles.com/orwell/articles/col-dystopia.htm |title=Archived copy |accessdate=19 March 2006 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20060326062103/http://www.netcharles.com/orwell/articles/col-dystopia.htm |archivedate=26 March 2006 }}, [https://books.google.com/books?vid=ISBN157181440X&id=3ye0vWc85eYC&pg=PA230&lpg=PA230&dq=John+Stuart+Mill+dystopia+1868])</ref> '''kakotopia''', '''cackotopia''', or '''anti-utopia''') ''is an imaginary community or society, that is undesirable or frightening''.<ref name=Merriam/><ref name=Oxford/> The literal translation, from its [[Greek language|Greek]] origin into the English language, reads as \"''not-good place''\"; an [[antonym]] of ''[[utopia]]''. Dystopian societies appear in many artistic works, most notably, in stories [[setting (narrative)|set]] in a future time-period. ''Dystopias'' are often characterized by [[dehumanization]],<ref name=Merriam>{{cite web|work=Merriam-Webster|publisher=Merriam-Webster, Inc.|title=Definition of \"dystopia\"|year=2012|url=http://www.merriam-webster.com/dictionary/dystopia}}</ref> [[totalitarian]] governments, ruthless [[megacorporation]]s, [[environmental disaster]],<ref name=Oxford>{{cite web|work=Oxford Dictionaries|publisher=Oxford University Press|title=Definition of \"dystopia\"|year=2012|url=http://oxforddictionaries.com/definition/english/dystopia?q=dystopia}}</ref> or other characteristics associated with a dramatic decline in society. ''Dystopian'' societies appear in many subgenres of fiction, oftentimes being used to draw attention to potential or real-world trends combined with societal issues. Examples of popular topics include: [[environmental issues|environmental]], [[cultural]], [[politics|political]], [[economics|economical]], [[religion|religious]], [[psychology|psychological]], [[ethics|ethical]], [[science|scientific]], and [[technology|technological]] issues; all of which, if left unaddressed, have the potential outcome of a dystopia.\n\n==List==\n{|class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Title !! Year !! class=\"unsortable\" | Comments !! class=\"unsortable\" | References\n|-\n|-Automata\n| ''[[The 10th Victim]]''\n| 1965\n| In the near-future, [[War|wars]] are avoided by giving people a chance to kill in the \u00a8''Big Hunt''\u00a8; the most popular form of entertainment. Based on [[Robert Sheckley]]'s short story, ''[[Seventh Victim]]'' (1953).\n| <ref name=playlist/>\n|-\n| ''[[12 Monkeys (film)|12 Monkeys]]''\n| 1995\n| A [[convict]] is sent back in time to gather information about a virus responsible for wiping out most of the human population. Based on [[Chris Marker]]'s short film, ''[[La Jet\u00e9e]]'' (1962).\n| <ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/2013/sep/02/terry-gilliam-zero-theorem-internet-breakdown-real-relationships|title=Terry Gilliam blames internet for the breakdown in 'real relationships'|last=Pulver|first=Andrew|newspaper=[[The Guardian]]|date=2 September 2013|accessdate=7 September 2013}}</ref><ref name=taste/><ref name=catholicism/>{{rp|34}}\n|-\n| ''[[1984 (1956 film)|1984]]''\n| 1956\n| A [[bureaucrat]] falls in love in a futuristic, totalitarian, surveillance state. ''Loosely'' based on [[George Orwell]]\u2019s novel, ''[[Nineteen Eighty-Four|Nineteen-Eighty-Four]]'' (1949).\n| <ref name=aaron>{{cite news| last =Aaronovitch| first =David|title =1984: George Orwell's road to dystopia| newspaper =BBC News Magazine| location =United Kingdom| publisher =The BBC|date =8 February 2013|u