t duplicate.\n| <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.allmovie.com/movie/v9110|work=Allm ovie|title=Cherry 2000|last=Dillard|first=Brian J.}}</ref>\n|-\n| ''[[Children of Men]]''\n| 2006\n| Directed by [[Alfonso Cuar\u00f3n]], based on [[P.D. James]]' 1992 [[The Children of Men|novel of the same name]]. In 2027, in a chaotic world in which women have become somehow infertile, a former activist agrees to help transport a miraculously pregnant woman to a sanctuary at sea.\n| <ref name=routledge/><ref name=rollingstonetop10/><ref name=miami/><ref name=prophecy>{{cite web|work=Huffington Post|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/john-w-whitehead/dystopian-films_b_901579.html|title=Fulfilling Orwell's Prophecy: 15 Futuristic Films You Should See|date=19 July 2011|first=John|last=Whitehead}}</ref>\n|-\n| ''[[City of Ember]]''\n| 2008\n| After a war on earth the remaining future generations are sent to an underground world to live until the earth surface can support life, an unfortunate set of circumstances keeps them underground for longer than planned but they eventually find the way out after 2 brave children discover the way.\n| <ref>{{cite journal |url= |last= Chang |first= Justin |title= Eye-popping 'Ember' burns out |journal= [[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] |location= New York |publisher= Penske Business Media |volume= 412 |issue= 9 |date= 13 October 2008 |page= 39}}</ref>\n|-\n| ''[[City of Lost Children]]''\n| 1995\n| French film directed by [[Jean-Pierre Jeunet]]. In a surrealist world, a scientist named Krank is kidnapping children to steal their dreams, in the hope that these dreams can slow or stop his aging process. When Krank and his clones kidnap Denree, his older brother One starts a searching to rescue.\n| <ref name=taste/>\n|-\n| ''[[A Clockwork Orange (film)|A Clockwork Orange]]''\n| 1971\n| Adapted from [[Anthony Burgess]]' 1962 [[A Clockwork Orange (novel)|novella of the same name]]. In a future [[England]] ruled by gangs, the government [[brainwashing|brainwashes]] one particular hoodlum into subservience.\n| <ref name=tropes/><ref name=rollingstonetop10/><ref>{{cite book|last=McDougal|first=Stuart Y.|title=Stanley Kubrick's A Clockwork Orange|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Uwj5qK-RUj0C&pg=PA1|date=7 July 2003|publisher=Cambridge University Press|isbn=978-0-521-57488-4}}</ref>\n|-\n| ''[[Cloud Atlas (film)|Cloud Atlas]]''\n| 2012\n| Adapted from the 2004 novel of the same name by David Mitchell. Set across six different eras (1849, 1936, 1973, 2012, 2144 and 2321), the movie tells the story a few group of souls crossing each other along different incarnations and how it changes the world according time passes.\n| <ref name=grimfuture/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://io9.com/5955079/is-cloud-atlas-an-unholy-mess-or-a-brilliant-masterpiece-yes|title=Is Cloud Atlas an unholy mess or a brilliant masterpiece? Yes.|first=Charlie Jane|last=Anders|date=26 October 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/daviddisalvo/2012/10/29/review-cloud-atlas-is-a-noble-disaster/|title=Review: 'Cloud Atlas' is a Noble Disaster|first=David|last=DiSalvo|date=29 October 2012}}</ref> <!-- http://www.slate.com/articles/arts/movies/2012/10/cloud_atlas_starring_tom_hanks_and_halle_berry_reviewed.html -->\n|-\n| ''[[Code 46]]''\n| 2003\n| A futuristic 'Brief Encounter', a love story in which the romance is doomed by genetic incompatibility.\n| <ref name=playlist/>\n|-\n| ''[[Colossus: The Forbin Project]]''\n| 1970\n| The film which is based upon [[Dennis Feltham Jones]]' science fiction novel ''[[Colossus (novel)|Colossus]]'' (1966), is about a massive American defense computer, named Colossus, after becoming [[Sentience|sentient]] logically follows its original directives to the dismay of its programmers by [[Cybernetic revolt|assuming control of the world]] and all human affairs for the good of mankind<ref>{{Tcmdb title|id=71253|title=Colossus: The Forbin Project}}</ref> during the [[Cold War]] threat of [[nuclear war]].<ref name=neolib/>\n| <ref name=neolib/><ref name=overlooked/><ref>{{cite web|last1=Wheeler Winston Dixon|first1=Ryan|title=Colossus \u2013 The Forbin Project \u2013 No Longer Sci-Fi|url=http://blog.unl.edu/dixon/2015/01/16/colossus-the-forbin-project-no-longer-sci-fi/|accessdate=9 September 2015|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://archive.is/20160124130740/http://blog.unl.edu/dixon/2015/01/16/colossus-the-forbin-project-no-longer-sci-fi/|archivedate=24 January 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last1=Westfahl|first1=Gary|title=The Greenwood Encyclopedia of Science Fiction and Fantasy: Themes, Works, and Wonders|date=2005|isbn=978-0313329500|page=482|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=3JXnz9x9sO4C&pg=PA482&lpg=PA482&dq=Colossus:+The+Forbin+Project+dystopia|accessdate=9 September 2015}}</ref>\n|-\n| ''[[The Congress (2013 film)|The Congress]]''\n| 2013\n| ''The Congress'' is a [[late capitalism|late-capitalist]] dystopia in which a corporate media behemoth \"Miramount\" has effectively usurped control of all human consciousness.<ref name=slateart/> In it an aging actress decides to [[Digital immortality|scan]] her body to sign over to Miramount Studios which allows the company to digitize every trait that she possesses and use it in any movie they choose. The hallucinogenic [[Films with live action and animation|live-action/animation]] film represents corporate interests taking advantage of the individual and was partly inspired by [[Stanis\u0142aw Lem]]'s novel ''[[The Futurological Congress]]''.\n| <ref name=slateart>{{cite web|last1=Stevens|first1=Dana|title=The Art House in Your Living Room|url=http://www.slate.com/articles/arts/movies/2014/08/the_congress_the_strange_little_cat_and_the_one_i_love_vod_film_reviews.html|accessdate=15 June 2015|date=8 August 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Barrett|first1=Michael|title=The Home Vidiot: January videos bring a dose of strangeness to awards season|url=http://www.sacurrent.com/sanantonio/the-home-vidiot-january-videos-bring-a-dose-of-strangeness-to-awards-season/Content?oid=2375458|accessdate=15 June 2015|date=21 January 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Glinter|first1=Ezra|title=The Revolution Will Be Animated|url=http://forward.com/culture/204755/the-revolution-will-be-animated/|accessdate=15 June 2015|date=28 August 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Pevere|first1=Geoff|title=The Congress: Toon tyranny or animated utopia?|url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/arts/film/film-reviews/the-congress-toon-tyranny-or-animated-utopia/article20248192/|newspaper=The Globe and Mail|accessdate=15 June 2015|date=29 August 2014}}</ref>\n|-\n| ''[[The Cybernetic Grandma]]''\n| 1962\n|  a 1962 Czechoslovakian stop motion puppet cartoon. It is a surreal science fiction-horror animation film, showing a dystopian situation where machines tend humans into a cybernetic lifestyle.\n| \n|-\n| ''[[Dark City (1998 film)|Dark City]]''\n| 1998\n| A man struggles with memories of his past, including a wife he cannot remember, in a nightmarish world with no sun and run by beings with telekinetic powers who seek the souls of humans.\n| <ref name=taste/><ref name=tropes/>\n|-\n| ''[[Dark Metropolis]]''\n| 2010\n| Mankind has lost a 300-year war against a genetically enhanced race that man created, abused and finally tortured. Now the descendants of that race - known as the 'Ghen' control the planet Earth from advanced underground cities.\n| <ref>{{cite web|first1=Michelle|last1=(Unknown)|title={ARC Review+Giveaway} Dark Metropolis by Jaclyn Dolamore|url=http://bookbriefs.net/2014/06/02/arc-reviewgiveaway-dark-metropolis-jaclyn-dolamore/|accessdate=13 June 2015|date=2 June 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Dark Metropolis|url=http://www.filmaffinity.com/en/film624359.html|publisher=[[FilmAffinity]]|accessdate=13 June 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Scheib|first1=Richard|title=Dark Metropolis|url=http://moria.co.nz/sciencefiction/dark-metropolis-2010.htm|accessdate=13 June 2015}}</ref>\n|-\n| ''[[Dawn of the Planet of the Apes]]''\n|2014\n|Ten years after the pandemic of the deadly [[Rise of the Planet of the Apes|ALZ-113 virus]], or Simian Flu, the worldwide human population has been drastically reduced, with only about one in five hundred genetically immune to the virus. Apes, with [[Genetic engineering|genetically]] [[Intelligence amplification|enhanced intelligence]] caused by the same virus, have started to build a civilization of their own. [[Caesar (Planet of the Apes)|Caesar]] is the [[Common chimpanzee|chimpanzee]] leader of an ape colony in the [[Muir Woods]] near San Francisco. Caesar's son Blue Eyes and his friend Ash encounter a man named Carver in the woods, who panics and shoots Ash, wounding him. Carver's party, led by Malcolm, arrive while a number of apes join Blue Eyes and Ash. Caesar orders the humans to leave, and they flee to their community in San Francisco, centered around \"the tower\", a partially finished skyscraper. Prompted by Koba, a scarred [[bonobo]] who holds a grudge against humans for experimental mistreatment. \n|<ref>{{Citation|last=Reeves|first=Matt|title=Dawn of the Planet of the Apes|date=11 July 2014|url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt2103281/|others=Gary Oldman, Keri Russell, Andy Serkis|accessdate=21 November 2017}}</ref>\n|-\n| ''[[The Day the Earth Caught Fire]]''\n| 1961\n| One of the classic apocalyptic films of its era, this film depicts the US and Russia unwittingly testing atomic bombs at the same time, altering the Earth's axis of rotation. \n| <ref name=gaze/>\n|-\n| ''[[Daybreakers]]''\n| 2009\n| In the year 2019, a plague has transformed almost every human into vampires. Faced with a dwindling blood supply, the fractured dominant race plots their survival.\n| <ref>{{cite news|last1=Pulver|first1=Andrew|title=Film review: Daybreakers|url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/2010/jan/07/daybreakers-review|newspaper=The Guardian|accessdate=13 June 2015|date=7 January 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite magazine|last1=McDonagh|first1=Maitland|title=Daybreakers - Film Review|url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/movie/daybreakers/review/29080|magazine=The Hollywood Reporter|accessdate=13 June 2015|date=14 October 2010}}</ref>\n|-\n| ''[[Dead End Drive-In]]''\n| 1986\n| A teenage couple is trapped in a drive-in theater which is really a concentration camp for societal rejects. The inmates are fed a steady diet of junk food, new wave music, drugs, and violent films.\n| <ref>{{cite journal|url=http://sensesofcinema.com/2012/64/dead-end-drive-in-brian-trenchard-smith-1986/|title=Dead End Drive-In (Brian Trenchard-Smith, 1986)|last=Buckmaster|first=Luke|journal=[[Senses of Cinema]]|date=September 2012|issue=64|accessdate=11 February 2014}}</ref>\n|-\n| ''[[Death Race (film)|Death Race]]''\n| 2008\n| Remake of the film ''[[Death Race 2000]]'' (1975). Ex-con Jensen Ames is forced by the warden of a notorious prison to compete in our post-industrial world's most popular sport: a car race in which inmates must brutalize and kill one another on the road to victory.\n| <ref>{{cite web|last1=West |first1=Jackson |title=\"Death Race\" shows why YouTube will kill us all |url=http://gawker.com/5042303/death-race-shows-why-youtube-will-kill-us-all |website=gawker.com |accessdate=13 June 2015 |date=27 August 2008 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150615045123/http://gawker.com/5042303/death-race-shows-why-youtube-will-kill-us-all |archivedate=15 June 2015 }}</ref>{{unreliable source?|date=June 2015}}\n|-\n| ''[[Death Race 2000]]''\n| 1975\n| The film takes place in a dystopian American society in the year 2000, where the murderous Transcontinental Road Race has become a form of national entertainment.\n| <ref name=playlist/><ref>{{cite news|title=Wheels On Film: Death Race 2000|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/motoring/wheelsonfilm/4227948/Wheels-On-Film-Death-Race-2000.html|newspaper=The Telegraph|accessdate=13 June 2015|date=13 January 2009}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Leith|first1=William|title=Death Race suffers from car trouble|url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/2008/oct/15/off-the-leith-death-race|accessdate=13 June 2015|date=15 October 2008|newspaper=The Guardian}}</ref><ref name=TVnews>{{cite news|last1=Rose|first1=Steve|title=From Network to Nightcrawler: why has Hollywood got it in for TV news?|url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/2014/oct/31/network-to-nightcrawler-tv-news-film-jake-gyllenhaal|newspaper=The Guardian|accessdate=13 June 2015|date=31 October 2014}}</ref>\n|-\n| ''[[Death Watch]]''\n| 1980\n| Based on the novel The Unsleeping Eye by David G. Compton, set in a future where death from illness has become extremely unusual. When the protagonist is diagnosed as having an incurable disease, she becomes a celebrity and is besieged by journalists.\n| <ref name=overlooked>{{cite web|url=http://www.pastemagazine.com/articles/2015/01/10-overlooked-classics-dystopian-films.html|work=Paste Magazine|title=10 Overlooked Classics: Dystopian Films|date=23 January 2015|first=Brogan|last=Morris}}</ref>\n|-\n| ''[[Demolition Man (film)|Demolition Man]]''\n| 1993\n| A long imprisoned ultra-violent criminal is brought out of suspended animation by a new \"perfect\" future society's leader as an unsanctioned solution to its unwanted dissidents. In response, a long imprisoned rogue cop is brought out of suspended animation by the new \"perfect\" future police department as their solution to the problem.\n| <ref name=gaze/><ref name=liberals>{{cite web|url=http://io9.com/5044657/best-future-dystopias-where-the-liberals-have-won|work=io9|title=Best Future Dystopias Where The Liberals Have Won|last=Anders|first=Charlie Jane|date=3 September 2008}}</ref>\n|-\n| ''[[Le Dernier Combat]]'' (English title: The Last Battle)\n| 1983\n| A dark vision of post-apocalyptic survival, the film was shot in black and white and contains only two words of dialogue. It depicts a world where people have been rendered mute by some unknown incident.\n| <ref>{{cite book|last1=Everett|first1=Wendy|title=The Seeing Century: Film, Vision and Identity|date=2000|isbn=9789042014848|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=lWRW74ZMm1MC&pg=PA136&lpg=PA136&dq=Le+Dernier+Combat+dystopia|accessdate=13 June 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Trencheva|first1=Elena|title=Bleak Future, Bleak Costume|url=https://www.academia.edu/3594205|accessdate=13 June 2015|date=2013}}</ref><ref name=paulbrazil>{{cite book|last1=McAuley|first1=Paul|title=Brazil|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=aEKVBQAAQBAJ&pg=PT10&dq=Le+Dernier+Combat+dystopi|accessdate=13 June 2015|isbn=9781844577958|date=31 October 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|work=AV Club|title=Luc Besson kickstarted his career with a striking, wordless doomsday movie|url=http://www.avclub.com/article/luc-besson-kickstarted-his-career-striking-wordles-205753|last=Dowd|first=A. A.|date=13 June 2014}}</ref>\n|-\n| ''[[District 9]]''\n| 2009\n| An extraterrestrial race forced to live in slum-like conditions on Earth suddenly finds a kindred spirit in a government agent who is exposed to their [[biotechnology]].\n| <ref name=sundance/><ref name=grimfuture/>\n|-\n| ''[[Divergent (film)|Divergent]]''\n| 2014\n|  Based on the adaption of [[Veronica Roth]]'s [[Divergent trilogy|novels of the same names]]. In a world divided by factions based on virtues, Tris learns she's Divergent and won't fit in.\n| <ref name=playlist>{{cite web|work=Indie Wire|url=http://blogs.indiewire.com/theplaylist/15-underseen-and-overlook-dystopian-futures-in-film-20140319|title=The Playlist: 15 Underseen And Overlooked Dystopian Futures In Film|first=Gabe|last=Toro|date=19 March 2014}}</ref><ref name=grimfuture/><ref name=wonttouch/><ref name=whyteens/><ref name=jstor/><ref name=freemarket/><ref name=peak/>\n|-\n| ''[[The Divergent Series: Insurgent]]''\n| 2015\n|  After the series of events and death of her parents in ''Divergent'', Tris Prior tries to figure out what the Abnegation were trying to protect and why the Erudite leaders will do anything to stop them.\n| <ref name=grimfuture/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://uproxx.com/movies/2015/03/the-divergent-series-insurgent-review/|work=Uproxx|last=Ryan|first=Mike|date=13 March 2015|title='The Divergent Series: Insurgent' Is So Much Better Than The First Movie}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/movie/insurgent/review/778586|work=Hollywood Reporter|last=Linden|first=Shen|title='Insurgent': Film Review|date=11 March 2015}}</ref>\n|-\n| ''[[Downstream (2010 film)|Downstream]]''\n| 2010\n| Takes place in a near-future dystopia where gasoline is scarce and a drifter tries to reach a rumored utopian city, Plutopia, powered by clean energy.\n| <ref>[http://www.sfbg.com/listing/2010/02/23/our-weekly-picks Our weekly picks], Cheryl Eddy, ''[[San Francisco Bay Guardian]]'', 23 February 2010 (retrieved 6 September 2010)</ref>\n|-\n| ''[[Dr. Mabuse the Gambler]]''\n| 1922\n| An exaggerated portrayal of [[Weimar Germany]] which the titular villain can exploit for power and profit.\n| <ref name=cambridgescifi>{{cite book|title=The Cambridge Companion to Science Fiction|editor1=James, Edward|editor2=Mendlesohn, Farah|page=82|year=2003|publisher=Cambridge University Press|isbn=9780521016575\n}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Film Notes: Dr. Mabuse: The Gambler|url=http://www.albany.edu/writers-inst/webpages4/filmnotes/fns00n9.html|publisher=New York State Writer's Institute|accessdate=22 March 2017}}</ref>\n|-\n| ''[[Dredd]]''\n| 2012\n| Adapted from the comic book of the same name. In a distant and irradiated future where judges and polices are the same corp, Judge Dredd and aspiring to Judge Cassandra Anderson become trapped in one of the several 200-storey tower block (named Megatowers) by Ma-Ma, a powerful and violent drug lady, to prevent Dredd dismantle her business and dominion in the tower block.\n| <ref name=grimfuture/><ref name=\"2012Empire\">{{cite web|first=Owen |last=Williams |title=Exclusive: John Wagner And Alex Garland Talk Dredd |url=http://www.empireonline.com/interviews/interview.asp?IID=1530 |publisher=[[Bauer Media Group]] |work=[[Empire (film magazine)|Empire]] |year=2012 |accessdate=5 September 2012 |archive-url=https://www.webcitation.org/6AeIhHk36?url=http://www.empireonline.com/interviews/interview.asp?IID=1530 |archivedate=13 September 2012 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Nothing To 'Dredd' About A New Action Adaptation|url=https://www.npr.org/2012/09/20/161272582/nothing-to-dredd-about-a-new-action-adaptation|publisher=NPR|accessdate=14 June 2015|date=20 September 2012}}</ref>\n|-\n| ''[[Elysium (film)|Elysium]]''\n| 2013\n| In this film [[wealth inequality]], the alienation of the super-rich and [[class conflict]] are taken to the extreme: in the year 2154, the very wealthy live on a man-made luxurious space station while the rest of the population resides on a ruined Earth. A man takes on a mission that could bring equality to the polarized worlds. It explores political and sociological themes such as immigration, [[Human overpopulation|overpopulation]], [[health care]], [[Exploitation of labour|exploitation]], the justice system, and [[social class]] issues.<ref name=\"Vulture\">{{cite web|last=Buchanan|first=Kyle|url=http://www.vulture.com/2013/04/elysium-matt-damons-action-movie-for-the-99.html|title=Elysium: Matt Damon's Action Movie for the 99%|publisher=Vulture|accessdate=10 April 2013}}</ref>\n| <ref name=grimfuture/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://grantland.com/features/the-disappointing-elysium-terrible-canyons/|work=Grantland|last=Morris|first=Wesley|date=8 August 2013|title=Future Imperfect}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Elysium|date=9 August 2013|work=Cinemalogue|last=Jorgenson|first=Todd|url=http://www.cinemalogue.com/2013/08/09/elysium/}}</ref>\n|-\n| ''[[The End of Evangelion]]''\n| 1997\n| When the dawn of the new millennium brings destruction on Earth by means of the seemingly all-powerful angels, the only hope for the future of the human race lies in Evangelions\u2014bio-engineered crafts created from the Angel's technology.\n| <ref name=miami/>\n|-\n| ''[[Ender's Game (film)|Ender's Game]]''\n| 2013\n| Based on the [[Ender's Game|novel of the same name]] by [[Orson Scott Card]].\n| <ref name=hate>{{cite web|work=The Vulture|url=http://www.vulture.com/2014/11/ya-dystopian-films-have-become-what-they-hate.html|title=YA Dystopian Films Have Become What They Hate|first=Nick|last=Schager|date=21 November 2014}}</ref>\n|-\n| ''[[Equalizer 2000]]''\n| 1987\n| One of the several [[low-budget film|low-budget movies]] inspired on [[Mad Max]] made in the 80s. Set in an Alaska a few hundred years later of a nuclear war, a ruthless and fascist vehicular group named The Ownership ruled by General MacLaine faces a rebellion that tries to destroy The Ownership to live free, but the rude Captain Slade leaves the group after Mayor Lawton kills Slade's father (The Ownership's field commander) and leaves him for dead, joining to the rebellion. Meeting Karen and her father Dixon, Slade and Dixon modify a firearm to create the massive-weapon Equalizer 2000, turning in one-man army to defeat Mayor Lawton and The Ownership.\n| | <ref>{{cite web|work= The Action Elite |date=16 January 2015|title= EQUALIZER 2000 (1987) REVIEW |url= https://theactionelite.com/equalizer-2000-1987-review/ |first=Eoin|last=Friel}}</ref>\n|-\n| ''[[Equals (film)|Equals]]''\n| 2015\n| Two people infected with a disease regain their ability to feel compassion and emotion in a society where emotions no longer exist.\n|<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.indiewire.com/2016/07/equals-review-kristen-stewart-drake-doremus-nicholas-hoult-1201705118/|title= 'Equals' Review: Kristen Stewart Is The Only Bright Spot In This Dull Dystopian Romance|last=Ehrlich |first= David |date=13 July 2016 |website= |publisher= |access-date=15 January 2017 |quote=}}</ref>\n|-\n| ''[[Equilibrium (film)|Equilibrium]]''\n| 2002\n| In a totalitarian future where all forms of feeling are illegal and citizens are required to take daily drug-injections to suppress emotion and encourage obedience, a man in charge of enforcing the law rises to overthrow the system.\n| <ref name=routledge/>\n|-\n| ''[[Escape from L.A.]]''\n| 1996\n| Sequel to the 1981 film, ''[[Escape from New York]]''. In 2013, Snake Plissken is sent to the turned-in-island Los Angeles after The Big One earthquake to rescue The President's daughter, kidnapped by the revolutionary group Shining Path lead by Cuervo Jones that it rules Los Angeles.\n| <ref name=grimfuture/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sfgate.com/movies/article/FILM-REVIEW-The-Ocean-Falls-Into-L-A-2971032.php|last=Stack|first=Peter|work=SFGate|title=FILM REVIEW -- The Ocean Falls Into L.A. / Drowned city stars with Kurt Russell in \"Escape' sequel|date=9 August 1996}}</ref>\n|-\n| ''[[Escape from New York]]''\n| 1981\n| In 1997, when the US President crashes into Manhattan, now a giant [[Incarceration in the United States#Security levels|maximum security prison]], a convicted bank robber named Snake Plissken is sent in for a rescue. It extrapolates the crime and decay of inner cities.<ref name=neolib/>\n| <ref name=tropes/><ref name=rollingstonetop10/>\n|-\n| ''[[eXistenZ]]''\n| 1999\n| Directed by [[David Cronenberg]]. As in Videodrome, Cronenberg gives his psychological statement about how humans react and interact with the technologies that surround them, in this case, the world of video games.\n| <ref name=jstor/>\n|-\n| ''[[Fahrenheit 451 (1966 film)|Fahrenheit 451]]''\n| 1966\n| Based on [[Ray Bradbury]]'s [[Fahrenheit 451|novel of the same name]]. In an oppressive future, a fireman whose duty is to destroy all books begins to question his task.\n| <ref name=tropes/><ref name=routledge/><ref name=prophecy/>\n|-\n| ''[[Fantastic Planet]]''\n| 1973\n| The story of this animated film, about humans living on a strange planet dominated by giant humanoid aliens who consider them animals, is based on the 1957 novel Oms en s\u00e9rie by French 