stor>{{cite web|url=http://daily.jstor.org/why-are-dystopian-films-on-the-rise-again/|title=WHY ARE DYSTOPIAN FILMS ON THE RISE AGAIN? Daily|last=Schmidt|first=Christopher|date=19 November 2014}}</ref>\n|-\n| ''[[The Hunger Games: Mockingjay \u2013 Part 2]]''\n| 2015\n| Directed by Francis Lawrence, based on Suzanne Collins' ''Mockingjay''.\n| \n|-\n| ''[[I Am Legend (film)|I Am Legend]]''\n| 2007\n| The third adaptation of [[Richard Matheson]]'s 1954 novel ''[[I Am Legend (novel)|I Am Legend]]''.\n| <ref name=tropes/><ref name=hungerstand/>\n|-\n| ''[[I, Robot (film)|I, Robot]]''\n| 2004\n| Adapted from the [[I, Robot|I, Robot series ]] by [[Isaac Asimov]]. An A.I. creates a potential dystopian future by logically applying the [[Zeroth Law of Robotics]] but is stopped.\n| <ref name=tropes/> \n|-\n| ''[[Idaho Transfer]]''\n| 1973\n| Directed by [[Peter Fonda]] in his directorial debut and starring [[Keith Carradine]].\n| <ref name=\"idaho\">{{cite web|title=Idaho Transfer|url=http://classicscifi.blogspot.com/2013/05/idaho-transfer.html|website=Classic Sci-Fi Movies|accessdate=13 May 2016}}</ref>\n|-\n| ''[[Idiocracy]]''\n| 2006\n| An average man is selected for a top-secret hibernation program. When he wakes up 500 years later to discover he's the smartest person in a radically [[Dumbing down|dumbed-down]] society.\n| <ref name=liberals/>\n|-\n| ''[[In Time]]''\n| 2011\n| In 2169, future people stop aging past 25 so time has become the universal currency traded between people. When the time \"bank account\" on an implanted clock reaches zero, that impoverished person \"times out\" and is euthanized. \n| <ref name=tropes/><ref name=hungerstand/>\n|-\n| ''[[The Inhabited Island]]''\n| 2009\n| Based on the 1969 book ''[[Prisoners of Power]]'' by [[Strugatskies]]. The most expensive [[Russian science fiction]] film to date (2015) is set on another planet, with a country that is ruled by a totalitarian regime that brainwashes its citizens by towers that send a special kind of radiation erected across the country.\n| <ref>{{cite web|title=Friday Night at the Kino: Obitaemy Ostrov (The Inhabited Island) (International Program)|url=http://calendar.ku.edu/index.php?option=eventview&ce_id=62688|accessdate=13 June 2015|date=September 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150615214839/http://calendar.ku.edu/index.php?option=eventview&ce_id=62688|archive-date=15 June 2015|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=The inhabited island movie review|url=https://webcache.googleusercontent.com/search?q=cache:6MlQ21LtKaYJ:https://cieboofludo.files.wordpress.com/2015/04/the-inhabited-island-movie-review.pdf|accessdate=13 June 2015}}</ref>\n|-\n| ''[[Invasion of the Body Snatchers]]''\n| 1956\n| Based on the novel The Body Snatchers by Jack Finney, depicts an extraterrestrial invasion that begins in the fictional California town of Santa Mira. Dr. Miles Bennell and his friends find a vegetal cocoons to discover that in really they're an alien vegetal race that duplicate human beings when these sleep.\n| <ref name=overlooked/>\n|-\n| ''[[Invasion of the Body Snatchers (1978 film)|Invasion of the Body Snatchers]]''\n| 1978\n| Remake of 1956 film, which is based on the novel The Body Snatchers by Jack Finney. A doctor realizes that an alien vegetal spores that they arrived to planet are supplanting human beings when they are asleep, consuming their bodies to replicate them and to be them.\n| <ref name=overlooked/>\n|-\n| ''[[Isle of Dogs (film)|Isle of Dogs]]''\n| 2018\n| A young boy searching for his dog after the species is banished to an island following the outbreak of a [[canine flu]].\n|\n|-\n| ''[[The Island (2005 film)|The Island]]''\n| 2005\n| A man goes on the run after he discovers that he is actually a \"harvestable being\", and is being kept as a source of replacement parts, along with others, in a facility.\n| <ref>{{cite web|work=Variety|url=https://variety.com/2005/film/reviews/the-island-4-1200524627/|title=Review: 'The I