onsumed by a nuclear holocaust, an adult John Connor who leads the war against machines looking for a young Kyle Reese between the Terminators' prisoners for that someday Reese travel back in time and meet his mother Sarah Connor.\n| <ref name=tropes/>\n|-\n| ''[[They Live]]''\n| 1988\n| Adapted from [[Ray Nelson]]'s play ''Eight O'Clock in the Morning''. A man who finds a sunglasses discovers that an extraterrestrial alien race live disguised as human beings, putting subliminal messages in all kind of books and advertising posters to summit human race.\n| <ref name=taste/><ref name=prophecy/>\n|-\n| ''[[Things To Come]]''\n| 1936\n| It is 30\u201340 years in the future, in the 1960s and 70s, and society has broken down after years of war. A contagious disease spreads throughout the globe. Brutal warlords rule with an iron fist. Technology stagnates. But a brotherhood of engineers and mechanics works to restore civilization.\n| <ref name=gaze/>\n|-\n|[[The Thinning]]\n|2016\n|Set in a [[dystopian future]] in which [[population control]] is enforced through a school [[aptitude test]]. Those who fail it are executed. Two high school students learn, to their horror, that the tests are rigged. They face many challenges and eventually make the ultimate sacrifice. Directed by [[Michael J. Gallagher (director)|Michael Gallagher]].\n|<ref>{{Citation|last=Gallagher|first=Michael J.|title=The Thinning|date=12 October 2016|url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt5254868/|others=Logan Paul, Peyton List, Lia Marie Johnson|accessdate=21 November 2017}}</ref>\n|-\n| ''[[The Time Machine (1960 film)|The Time Machine]]''\n| 1960\n| Film adoption of [[H. G. Wells]]' novel ''[[The Time Machine]]'' (1895). A scientist travels 700,000 years into the future and finds the world divided between humans and strange beings.\n| <ref>{{cite web|last1=Finn|first1=Natalie|title=The Birds Star Rod Taylor Dead at 84; Veteran Actor's Breakthrough Was 1960 Epic The Time Machine|url=http://de.eonline.com/news/612773/the-birds-star-rod-taylor-dead-at-84-veteran-actor-s-breakthrough-was-1960-epic-the-time-machine|website=eonline.com|accessdate=13 June 2015|date=8 January 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Keough|first1=Peter|title=Time traveling on screen|url=https://www.bostonglobe.com/arts/movies/2014/03/01/time-traveling-screen/lJogDnPoMAVv6nPPZlo0aO/story.html|newspaper=The Boston Globe|accessdate=13 June 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Valentin|first1=Mel|title=Cinematical Seven: Of Time Travel and Paradoxes (Among Other Things)|url=http://news.moviefone.com/2011/03/31/time-travel-paradoxes-in-movies/|accessdate=13 June 2015|date=31 March 2011}}</ref>\n|-\n| ''[[THX 1138]]''\n| 1971\n| Set in the 25th century, the story centers around a man and a woman who rebel against their rigidly controlled society. Also the first film by director [[George Lucas]].\n| <ref name=tropes/><ref name=prophecy/><ref name=liberals/>\n|-\n| ''[[Total Recall (1990 film)|Total Recall]]''\n| 1990\n| Loosely based on [[Philip K. Dick]]'s short story \"[[We Can Remember It for You Wholesale]]\" (1966). A jackhammer worker named Douglas Quaid that goes to a travel agency to be implanted with the false remember of a vacations in planet Mars discovers that all his life and his own identity could be another false remember.\n| <ref name=show/>\n|-\n| ''[[Total Recall (2012 film)|Total Recall]]''\n| 2012\n| Remake of [[Total Recall (1990 film)|the 1990 film of the same name]].\n| <ref name=grimfuture/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://articles.chicagotribune.com/2012-08-02/entertainment/sc-mov-0731-total-recall-20120801_1_total-recall-hover-car-chase-underworld-films|work=Chicago Tribune|last=Phillips|first=Michael|title='Total Recall': Remember this?|date=2 August 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|work=SF Gate|url=http://www.sfgate.com/movies/article/Total-Recall-review-Memory-lapse-3757549.php|title='Total Recall' review: Memory lapse|last=Biancolli|first=Amy|date=2 August 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|work=